INSERT INTO candrepresentatives VALUES (72,'Villanueva','Joel Emmanuel',NULL,546,0,'candrepresentatives - joel emmanuel villanueva.jpg','0000-00-00','','','','','','[Source <A HREF=\"http://www.cibac.org/about.html\">http://www.cibac.org/about.html</A>]\r\n<P>\r\nIn the Philippines, there seems to be a tendency for many to doubt the capabilities of the youth. Believing that somehow, potential to accomplish great deeds is directly proportional to age. If that were true, then the first representative of CIBAC could not possibly exist. Joel Villanueva, all of 25 years old, has worked hard to make his mark in society. As the current managing director of ZOE TV Channel 11, Joel has been the moving force behind ZOE\'s thrust to provide quality programming for millions of viewers. In addition, he is the chairman of the Kristianong Kabataan Para Bayan (KKB) and the Ministry of HELPS, a socio-civic group providing assistance to calamity victims. He was also a recepient of the Gloria Macapagal Arroyo leadership Award in 1996 as well as a 2-time RP Youth member, representing the country in international basketball competitions. \r\n<P>\r\nBut perhaps his most laudable trait is that he does not find any reason to rest on his laurels. Instead, he has turned his attention towards the people\'s fight against a formidable foe - corruption. Joel is offering his youth and desire to rid the government of this scourge which has been thought by many skeptics as an unsolvable problem. A quixotic spirit in this young man? Perhaps. But that\'s what brought him this far, and would serve him well as the first representative of CIBAC.','','','','',0,20010418102805,'','','','',0,0,'N');
INSERT INTO candrepresentatives VALUES (73,'Bernardo','Kim',NULL,546,0,'candrepresentatives - kim bernardo.jpg','0000-00-00','','','','','','[Source <A HREF=\"http://www.cibac.org/about.html\">http://www.cibac.org/about.html</A>]\r\n<P>\r\nLately, there has been a call to scrutinize media and showbiz candidates running for public office. Many seem to feel that these candidates simply make use of their popularity and their connections with media to catapult them into office without any real capacity to hold it. A skeptic would be quick about dismissing Kim as a CIBAC representative. Pretty, charming and outspoken, she could easily fit stereotypes made to show why media personalities should not be allowed to hold office. At least, on the surface, that is. It takes a closer look to reveal that Kim is actually be one of those who would actually insure a responsive, dynamic system of government that the people deserve. \r\n<P>\r\nKim Bernardo Lokin is a dedicated broadcast journalist who has steadfastly upheld her commitment to educate and inform the public on issues of national importance. For nearly a decade, Kim Bernardo-Lokin covered major news events enabling her to be familiar with key branches of government ---- Malacanang, Senate, Department of Justice and the NBI. As senior Senate reporter, Kim anchored ABS-CBN News Channel\'s Senate At Work from 1994-1995, giving the viewers a daily update of activities at the Upper House. \r\n<P>\r\nIn 1996, Kim was tapped to anchor the daily business program \"Stock Market Live\" also at the ABS CBN News Channel (ANC) a post she held for three years before getting her break as a primetime current affairs anchor of \"Moneywise\" a business magazine program which she hosted with Gilbert Remulla.','','','','',0,20010418103020,'','','','',0,0,'N');
INSERT INTO candrepresentatives VALUES (74,'Martinez','Atty. Jesus',NULL,546,0,'candrepresentatives - atty jesus martinez.jpg','0000-00-00','','','','','','[Source <A HREF=\"http://www.cibac.org/about.html\">http://www.cibac.org/about.html</A>]\r\n<P>\r\nSome say it is impossible in Philippine politics to find a successful marriage of good, moral values and political acumen in today\'s candidates. If that is true, then CIBAC truly is fortunate. Its third candidate, Atty. Jess Martinez, not only has both, but also manages to get his ideals across in a very down-to-earth and affable manner. He is remarkable in the sense that he has no puffed-up sense of self-importance about him, as many political hopefuls often try to project. His firm handshake and ever-present smile give an impression that he is just another citizen who is willing to serve if given a chance. It is an impression that is nothing but correct. \r\n<P>\r\nBorn in Manila to parents Jesus and Winifred Martinez, Jess has never shown anything but his competence and willingness to serve throughout his life. A lawyer by profession, he has handled many litigation cases for various local and foreign corporations for 15 years. In the political arena, he has been a former board member and later vice-mayor of Negros Oriental, where he served his constituents with the zeal expected of a servant of the public. \r\n<P>\r\nJess is also a lay minister of the Community Church of Las Pinas and Fil-American Church in Long Beach, U.S.A. He is married to Cheryl Lynn Jubela-Martinez and they have three children, Michelle Lynn, Monica, and Jesus Gianpaolo III.','','','','',0,20010418103230,'','','Jess','',0,0,'N');
INSERT INTO candrepresentatives VALUES (75,'Biazon','Rufino',NULL,466,177,'candrepresentatives - rufino biazon.jpg','0000-00-00','','','[Source <A HREF=\"http://www.ruffybiazon.com/platform.htm\">http://www.ruffybiazon.com/platform.htm</A>] <BR><BR>\r\n<B>Education</B>\r\n<OL> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Development of an Enhanced Public Pre-School System, Special Education Schools, and Adult \r\nElementary and High Schools</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Strengthen curriculum and improve teaching aids/facilities for public elementary and secondary schools to uplift standards and competitiveness of students</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Introduction of Information Technology subjects in primary and secondary schools</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Introduce Entrepreneurship Subjects in Elementary and Secondary Schools</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Information Technology Skills Training For Public School Teachers</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Establishment of OJT/Practicum Program for Secondary and Tertiary Schools in Muntinlupa-Based Offices</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Inculcation of Values-Oriented Education</LI> \r\n</OL>\r\n<B>Health</B> \r\n<OL>\r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Improvement and modernization of facilities for public / government hospitals, health centers and clinics</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Philhealth/Medicare coverage for more citizens of the city</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Establishment of local health code that address the needs of the times</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Inclusion of nutrition programs for public schools</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Institutionalization of public pre-natal healthcare for expectant mothers</LI> \r\n</OL>\r\n<B>Housing</B> \r\n<OL>\r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Establishment of In-City Socialized Housing</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Establishment of Local Housing Board</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Relocation of Informal Settlers in Muntilupa City</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Creation of Department of Housing and Urban Development</LI> \r\n</OL>\r\n<B>Livelihood and Business</B> \r\n<OL>\r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Promotion of Entrepreneurship</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Skills Training and Education Programs Geared Towards Entrepreneurship</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Creation of a Friendly Environment for Business, Especially  Small and Medium Scale Enterprises</LI> \r\n</OL>\r\n<B>Public Services</B> \r\n<OL>\r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Computerization of Public Services to Enable E-Commerce Transactions with Government</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Promotion of “Transaction By Mail” for Government Services</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">More Efficient and Effective Traffic Management</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Establishment of a Modernized Muntinlupa Emergency Response Team</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Equipment Upgrade for Muntinlupa Police Force</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Improvement of Water Supply Services</LI> \r\n</OL>\r\n<B>Urban Planning and Environment</B> \r\n<OL>\r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Formulation of Comprehensive Land Use Policy</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Review of City Zoning Ordinances</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Creation of 10-Year Urban Master Plan For The City subject to review and renewal every 5 years</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Establishment of “Green Areas” and Nature Preserves in the City</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Comprehensive Mapping of the City</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Updating Street Signs for National and Local Roads in the  City</LI>  \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Appropriate planning to address the growing traffic</LI>                                  problem and floods.\r\n</OL>\r\n  \r\n\r\n<B>Information Technology</B> \r\n<OL>\r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Computerization of the Local Government of Muntinlupa from Barangay To City Level</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Establishment of MuntiNet --- A network of local government offices to enhance online transactions</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Internet Access for all public schools</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Installation of Infrastructure Requirements for Higher      Bandwidth Capacity in Muntinlupa</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Strengthening laws on online transactions and penalizing cybercrimes</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Incentives for Information Technology Companies to Invest   in Muntinlupa</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Establishment of a Geogrpahic Information System in      Muntinlupa</LI> \r\n</OL>\r\n  \r\n\r\n<B>Socio-Political Reforms</B> \r\n<OL>\r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Establishment of Sectoral Representation by Election in       City Council</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Creation of Multi-Sectoral Anti-Graft Council</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Institutionalization of Values-Oriented Training for Public      Servants</LI> \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Computerization of Elections</LI>  \r\n<LI TYPE=\"a\">Reforming the Party List System</LI> \r\n</OL>','','','[Source <A HREF=\"http://www.ruffybiazon.com/profile.htm\">http://www.ruffybiazon.com/profile.htm</A>]\r\n<P>\r\nThe youngest of three children of Senator Rodolfo Biazon, Ruffy is not a newcomer in public service. \r\n<P>\r\nFrom his birth in Cavite Naval Station to his stay in Fort Bonifacio from less than a year old to his full maturity twenty three years later, he has seen and even been a part of countless civic action missions conducted by his father’s unit in the AFP. With his father’s strong leadership influence, he led similar activities in school, where he was actively involved in organizations and the student council. In the latter years of then General Biazon’s colorful career, Ruffy spent hours discussing with his father the intricacies of politics and public service, driven by the same fervor that characterized his writings in the school newspaper as an editor. \r\n<P>\r\nAfter high school, Ruffy dreamt of becoming a doctor with the noble intention of serving the people. As a pre-med course, he entered the University of Santo Tomas in and took up Medical Technology as a pre-med course. But fate had a different story for him. After his four years in UST, his life took a turn towards a different direction, although with the same objective---serving the people. \r\n<P>\r\nWhen he got out of college in 1991, he was appointed by then President Corazon Aquino to be a member of the Board of Directors of the Videogram Regulatory Board (VRB) representing the youth. Acting in a similar function as the MTRCB (Movie and Television Ratings and Classification Board), the VRB rates and classifies videogram materials, which are essentially those in video shops and video clubs. \r\n<P>\r\nWhen his father, then newly retired Chief of Staff of the AFP, first ran for senator  in 1992, he was appointed as Operations Director of the campaign organization. Although the campaign organization was not well funded and staffed by newcomers in politics, Ruffy was able draw up and implement and effective operations plan. As fate would have it, his father won a seat in the Senate. Immediately after that victory, Ruffy asked to organize the office due to his organizing skills, with the condition that he will continue on the medical school. But the exposure to being able to directly bring public service and the complexity of politics lured him to stay. \r\n<P>\r\nAs Chief of Staff of the Office of Senator Biazon, he practically was the right hand man of the senator. Aside from managing the daily administration of the office, he was also tasked to formulate projects for the Office’s public service programs. He was also the Chief Political Officer, to which he was delegated the task of liaising with other politicians, government agencies and private institutions. More importantly, he supervised the Legislative Staff, the group in the office that dealt with the primary task of a Senator---lawmaking. As such, he was responsible in leading the research and drafting of several important bills of the senator at that time such as the bill mandating the infusion of computer literacy subjects in all public elementary and high schools. \r\n<P>\r\nIn the 1995 elections, Ruffy was designated as Campaign Manager of Senator Biazon for his re-election bid. Although the campaign was effectively and efficiently run, the lack of campaign funds to match those spent by traditional moneyed politicians during the counting allowed Senator Biazon to be victimized by Dagdag-Bawas operators. For Ruffy, it opened an opportunity for him to go to Medical School. \r\n<P>\r\nBut as fate would have it, he was recruited by then newly-elected Senator Sergio Osmeña III to be his Chief Legislative Officer, tasked with heading the group which performed the lawmaking functions of the office. Ruffy used his previous experience to draw up an efficient team which became responsible in supporting Senator Osmeña in his legislative work. Landmark bills such as the Retail Trade Act and Public Services Act marked the output of the team. The investigation into the questionable Marconi Radar Contract was one of the important works of the team led by Ruffy which resulted into the cancellation of the contract. Another was the investigation into the series of sea tragedies which revealed the anomalies being done in the maritime agencies in the government. \r\n<P>\r\nTo prepare for Senator Biazon’s bid to return to the Senate in 1998, Ruffy resigned from the Office of Senator Osmeña in 1997 and prepared the groundwork for the campaign. Drawing on his organizing skills, political acumen and previous experience, Ruffy as Campaign Manager successfully steered the campaign of Senator Biazon to victory. \r\n<P>\r\nOnce again, Ruffy occupies the position of Chief of Staff of a senator’s office. More seasoned and mature this time around, he has taken on his role with much gusto. Once again, he has led the legislative staff of Senator Biazon to perform beyond the senator’s expectations. Effective management of human and material resources has brought about an effective and efficient office, with outputs surpassing those of other senators. \r\n<P>\r\nIn July of 2000, the Philippines played host to the 3rd Conference of the Global Parliamentarians on Habitat, an organization of parliamentarians and legislators from all over the world. Ruffy’s experience and skill in logistics management was once more tapped when he was appointed Director for Administration and Logistics of the conference secretariat. Without a hitch, the conference was conducted successfully, with more than 300 representatives from more than a hundred countries attending.  \r\n<P>\r\nBut the most important contribution of Ruffy to the senator’s office are the innovations and public service programs he has initiated. Being an avid information technology hobbyist (he is proficient in webpage design, computer graphics and multimedia applications), he has introduced computerization into the senator’s office making it one of the best equipped offices in the senate. He also provides the senator with insight on information technology, enabling the Senator to formulate proposals in the field of computerization. \r\n<P>\r\nBeing a resident of Muntinlupa, Ruffy formulated Compu.T.E.R.S. Project (Computer Training for Educators and Resources for Students Project) in Muntinlupa schools. Upon the recommendation of Ruffy, an initial amount of Three Million Pesos from Senator Biazon’s CDF was released for the purchase of computers for Muntinlupa National High School and Pedro E. Diaz High School and software training for the teachers. A second allocation amounting to Ten Million Pesos was released for the Compu.T.E.R.S. Project which would provide computers to all the four public high schools and fifteen public elementary schools plus software training for 740 public school teachers. Ruffy has also implemented an Internet Use Seminar for the students and teachers of Pedro Diaz High School, in preparation for the next project, the Internet Connection Project for high schools. \r\n<P>\r\nHaving gone around the country since 1992 delivering services in behalf of the senator, Ruffy has chosen to concentrate on the City of Muntinlupa. With his active participation in the legislative process since 1992, is knowledgeable about a wide range of issues, particularly those about information technology, education, public order and security, national defense, urban development and housing. \r\n<P>\r\nHis exposure in the Committee on Housing, Urban Planning and Resettlement which Senator Biazon chairs has given rise to his concern for those in the urban poor sector, particularly in Muntinlupa. He has formed MRB, Muntinlupa para sa Reproma at Bayanihan, a group that immerses itself in the urban poor communities of Muntinlupa and other sectors like the youth and the women, to get first hand information about the prevailing issues in those sectors to come up with legislative proposals that meet their needs. In addition, MRB has conducted numerous regular public service projects such as medical missions, water supply and support to activities of youth and community organizations. \r\n<P>\r\nHe has also initiated the “I Care for Day Care Project” of the Office of Senator Biazon, which benefits all 46 day care centers under the supervision of Muntinlupa Social Welfare Department. \r\n<P>\r\nIn his personal capacity, he is a director in ZONTAR Manpower Agency and Black Stallion Security Agency, both of which he is one of the incorporators.','','ruffy@ruffybiazon.com','8093132','0919-2015658',0,20010418130436,'','','Ruffy','',0,0,'N');
