INSERT INTO candrepresentatives VALUES (867,'De Los Angeles, Jr.','Celso','G',465,162,'','1952-08-06','<PRE>\r\nSeptember 1991	:	Georgetown Univeristy, Washington D.C.\r\n				Legal Assistant Program \r\n\r\n1974-1976		:	Asian Institute of Management\r\n				Master in Business Administration\r\n\r\n1970-1974		:	Ateneo de Manila Univeristy\r\n				BS Business Management\r\n\r\n1967-1970		:	Ateneo de Manila University\r\n				High School Graduate\r\n\r\n1960-1967		:	Ateneo de Manila University\r\n				Grade School Graduate \r\n</PRE>','','Legislative Agenda of Boy Seseng<BR>\r\n<P>\r\nI. Enactment of Laws\r\n<P>\r\n1. Livelihood and Job Creation <BR>\r\n<P>\r\n“Shoe Export Processing Zone Law” – law to declare Marikina City as an export processing zone for the Shoe industry to encourage the return and establishment of shoe factories in Marikina where they can import, free from taxes, raw materials and equipment for their production, thereby substantially reducing the cost of production.\r\n<P>\r\n“Marikina Shoebank” – law creating a shoe bank that shall service the financial needs of shoe manufacturers, small and big entrepreneurs, as well as the shoe laborers.\r\n<P>\r\n2. Education <BR>\r\n<P>\r\n“Public School Computerization Law” – law mandating Information Technology as part of the curriculum in all public high schools, providing computers on all public schools and allocating the budgetary requirements thereof, with the aim that all public high school graduates, even without college education, shall have basic computer skills. \r\n<P>\r\n3. Health <BR>\r\n<P>\r\n“Comprehensive Health Insurance Law” – law requiring Cities to set aside portion of its city budget in providing a health care insurance program for its residents, with the aim of extending a subsidized insurance premium payment for a heallth/medicare program to all residents of the City.\r\n<P>\r\n4. Housing <BR>\r\n<P>\r\n“Housing Program Devolution Law” – a law that will devolve or delegate to Cities the mass housing program of the National Government, empowering Cities to enter into mass housing projects to be financed by the National Government.\r\n<P>\r\n5. Crime Prevention <BR>\r\n<P>\r\n“Extended Illegal Drugs Law” – law amending existing law on illegal drugs by increasing the coverage and penalty for illegal possession.\r\n<P>\r\n6. Tax Alleviation <BR>\r\n<P>\r\n“Estate/Inheritance Exemption Law” – law to exempt estates or properties left by the deceased worth One Million Pesos (P1,000,000) and below from payment of Estate/Inheritance taxes.\r\n“Capital Gains Tax Exemption Law” – law providing the exemption from payment of Capital Gains Tax of the sale or transfer of property valued at Five Hundred Thousand Pesos (P500,000.00) or below as well as providing for a one-time tax exemption from Capital Gains Tax of a sale of a property of a senior citizen.\r\n<P>\r\nII. Local Concerns\r\n<P>\r\n1. Creation of Marikina Foreign Trade Mission <BR>\r\n<P>\r\nCreation of core group that will administer the Foreign Trade Mission for the city. Their main task is to promote Marikina Products specifically the shoe making industry to global market and encourage foreign investors to invest in Marikina.\r\n<P>\r\nThis will strengthen and flourish the Marikina business sector, and will provide employment to the many Marikenos.  \r\n<P>\r\n2. Training Center For the Youth <BR>\r\n<P>\r\nEmpowering the youth through an information technology by establishing a Training Center with competent instructors, conducive and complete learning facilities.\r\n<P>\r\nThis will give chance to less fortunate families whose desire for their child is to acquire value education. The training center will provide scholarships to qualified youth of the city, giving them the opportunity to learn today’s demand for information technology, so that they can contriute more, not only to the city but to the country as a whole.\r\n<P>\r\n3. Micro-Finance Program <BR>\r\n<P>\r\nDevelop a Lending Institute that will provide immediate cash loan for small-scale businesses with minimal interest and easy payment scheme.\r\n<P>\r\n4. Health Income Benefit For Senior Citizen <BR>\r\n<P>\r\nProvide Senior Citizen ages 45-65 years old the benefit of having FREE medical assistance and P500.00 cash benefit per day of necessary confinement for every illness for 365 days.\r\n<P>\r\n5. Personal Accisent Insurance For Pedicab, Tricycle & Jeepney Drivers <BR>\r\n<P>\r\nFREE accident insurance will be made available for pedicab, tricycle and jeepney drivers.\r\n<P>\r\nThis will assure them of P10,000 cash benefit in case of accidental death, and P5,000 up to P10,000 for accidental dismemberment.\r\n<P>\r\n6. Drug Prevention Program <BR>\r\n<P>\r\nDevelop drug prevention programs for the entire city. Concentrating on massive campaigns to scrap drug dependencies and avoidance. Enhancing the youth’s participation in various community projects and programs that will discourage them in using or even getting involved with illegal drugs.','<PRE>\r\n1998-Present	:	Chairman & CEO, Legacy Scholarship & Pension Plans, Inc.\r\n			1438 Legacy-SPPI Bldg. Quezon Ave., Q.C.\r\n\r\n1996-Present	:	Chairman & CEO, Scholarship Plan Philippines, Inc. \r\n			1438 Legacy-SPPI Bldg. Quezon Ave., Q.C.\r\n\r\n1996-Present	:	President, CGA Security Services\r\n			1438 Legacy-SPPI Bldg. Quezon Ave., Q.C.\r\n\r\n1996-2000	:	Chairman of the Board, Banco Paranaque\r\n			Parc Chateau Bldg., Ortigas Ctr., Pasig City\r\n\r\n1999-2000	:	Chairman, Executive Committee, First Interstate Bank\r\n			Karanga, Leyte\r\n\r\n2000		:	Chairman, Executive Committee, Bank of East Asia\r\n			Mingianilla, Cebu \r\n\r\n2000		:	Chairman, Executive Committee, Bank of Carmen\r\n			Carmen, Cebu\r\n\r\n2000		:	Chairman, Executive Committee, Bank of Pili\r\n			Pili, Camarines Sur\r\n\r\n1992-1996	:	President, UHF TV Channel 56\r\n			Honolulu, Hawaii\r\n\r\n1987-1992	:	Administrator, Pollit & Pollit Law Offices\r\n			Los Angeles, California\r\n\r\n1982-1984	:	Chairman & President, Synergy Capital Fusion Corp.\r\n			Makati, Metro Manila\r\n\r\n1983-Present	:	Chairman & President, Agricultural Mgt. & Dev. Corp.\r\n			206 J.P. Rizal St., Marikina City\r\n\r\n1982-1983	:	Director, Federated Thrift Bank\r\n			Guiguinto, Bulacan\r\n\r\n1982-1983	:	Director, Thrift Savings & Loan Bank\r\n\r\n1982-1983	:	Rural Bank of Calumpit, Inc. \r\n\r\n</PRE>','','<P>\r\nWho is Boy Seseng de los Angeles?\r\n<P>\r\nCelso Gancayco de los Angeles<BR>\r\n“Boy Seseng”<BR>\r\nDate of birth: August 6, 1952<BR>\r\nAddress: 206 J.P. Rizal St., Sta. Elena, Marikina City<BR>\r\nMarried to: Concepcion Arguelles Panlilio<BR>\r\nChildren: Martin Nicolo P. de los Angeles<BR>\r\nPaolo Vicente P. de los Angeles  <BR>\r\n<P>\r\nCelso Gancayco de los Angeles, Jr. also known as “Boy Seseng” is the great grandson of the founder of the Shoe Industry, Laureano “Kapitan Moy” Guevara. He is a native Marikeno. His father, the late Dr. Celso Guevara de los Angeles or “Dr. Seseng” was a very much-loved physician in Marikina. He was one of the internationally well respected authorities in the field of pulmonary medicine. In Marikina, he was often referred to as “Doktor ng Bayan”. The mother of Boy Seseng is Purita Gancayco de los Angeles. She is still very active in the Catholic Women’s League, where she was the former National Director. She is also a trustee of the Sandigan Foundation. Boy Seseng’s grandfather on his father’s side, the late Don Servando Manahan de los Angeles ran for Congress in the 2nd district of the Province of Rizal.\r\n<P>\r\nMr. Celso G. de los Angeles, Jr., more popular known as “Boy Seseng” hailed from Marikina, the shoe capital of the Philippines. His Father, a dedicated physician was fondly called by his patients and friends as Dr. Seseng and his mother, Purita Gancayco de los Angeles who isstill living at their family house where he grew up in Brgy. Sta. Elena is known in the neighborhood as Dona Purita. The desire of his loving parents to provide him a better life in the future sent him to an exclusive school, Ateneo de Manila University where he completed his education from grade school to college. He pursued his studies and took up his Masters in Business Administration at the Asian Institute of Management, the country’s premier school in Management.\r\n<P>\r\nBoy Seseng has also his ups and downs but he believes that there is an opportunity in every crisis. He realized how much more persons can do it if they go beyond what appears to be their limits. “If you dreamed the best for yourself, you usually get,” as he often emphasized to his employees. His experiences in the USA for almost 14 years where he was even forced to apply as a security guard and as a gasoline attendant served as an inspiration and encouragement for his work force. And while working, he took time to study and finish a course in Free Legal Administration Management at Georgetown University in Washinton D.C.\r\n<P>\r\nIn 1996, when Mr. Celso G. de los Angeles, Jr. returned to the Philippines, he was welcomed by an offer to venture in the pre-need business and joined a fast growing educational plan company, Scholarship Plan Philippines Inc., as Chairman and CEO. Although he did not know the industry very well, he considered it as a challenge, and his financial expertise had gained him a firm base in this new endeavor. However, he realized that a one-product company does not only limit its market share but the profit margin as well and on December 5, 1998 Celso G. de los Angeles, Jr. acquired Legacy Plans Inc., as majority owner and launched the most competitive pension plan in the market.\r\n<P>\r\nAs a banker and a businessman, Mr. Celso G. de los Angeles, Jr., inspired by his great grandfather, Don Laureano “Kapitan Moy” Guevarra who set up the first shoe industry, has a special concern for the shoe industry and putting up a Marikina Shoe bank partly owned by shoe manufacturers and partly owned by the government is his most cherished dream. He stressed that shoemakers in Marikina if given the right support can craft shoes and accessories that could compete in the fashion centers of Paris, London, New Yorkm and Tokyo and even penetarate the global market.\r\n<P>\r\nHis outstanding performance attained through the years will serve as benchmarks for greater achievements ahead. His innovative management, pioneering efforts and the commitment to the business will surely lead to futher improve performance, set higher standards and enhance human resources capability particularly in the fields of marketing to face greater challenges and set the tone for the next millennium.','Marikina City','bosesnatin@hotmail.com','','6461575',2,20010508105210,'','','Boy Seseng','',0,0,'N');
