posium on \r\nEquipping Southeast Asian Women Managers for the \r\n90\'s,<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, 6 March 1991. \r\n<BR>Corruption Prevention Strategies in Developing Countries, Keynote \r\nSpeaker,<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fourth International Anti-Corruption \r\nConference, Sydney, Australia, 13 November 1989. <BR><B><BR>CONFERENCES AND \r\nPROGRAMS</B>: <BR><BR>Fellow, Williamsburg Conference, Chiangmai, Thailand, \r\n1990. <BR>Fellow, International Visitor Program, Washington, D.C. and Los \r\nAngeles, 1989. <BR>Fellow, Special Visits Program, Sydney and Canberra, \r\nAustralia. <BR>Chairperson, 13th Roundtable on Current Problems of International \r\nHumanitarian Law,<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Remo, Italy, 1988. \r\n<BR>Philippine Delegate, Interpol General Assembly Session, Nice, France, 1987. \r\n<BR>Secretary-General, ASEAN Women Judges Conference, Manila, 1987. <BR>Fellow, \r\nStanford University, Palo Alto, California, 1985. <BR>Philippine Delegate, First \r\nInternational Seminar-Workshop on Managing Delay in the Courts, Manila, 1983. \r\n<BR>Chairperson, Second Philippine Goodwill Mission to the Republic of China, \r\n1968. <BR>Philippine Delegate, First Southeast Asian and Australasian Law \r\nStudents\' Seminar, Singapore, 1967. <BR><BR><B>PROFESSIONAL ORGANIZATIONS</B>: \r\n<BR><BR>Phi Kappa Phi International Honor Society <BR>Pi Gamma Mu International \r\nHonor Society <BR>Integrated Bar of the Philippines <BR>U.P. Law Alumni \r\nAssociation <BR>U.P. Women Lawyers\' Circle <BR>Philippine Society of \r\nInternational Law <BR>Fellows of the Asia Foundation <BR>California Judicial \r\nCollege Alumni Association <BR>Association of TOWNS Awardees <BR>Alumni \r\nAssociation of the Academy of American International Law <BR>Honorary member, \r\nZonta International of Makati <BR>Honorary member, Manila Lakambini Lions Club \r\n<BR>Honorary member, Philippine Military Academy Alumni Association, Inc. \r\n<BR><BR><B>PUBLICATIONS</B>: <BR><BR><B>A. BOOKS</B>: <BR><BR><B>Law</B>: \r\n<BR>International Law, With Philippine Cases and Materials and ASEAN \r\nInstruments.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Central Professional Books, Inc., \r\n1999. <BR>International Law (With Jorge \r\nCoquia).<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Central Professional Books, Inc., 3rd \r\ned. 1998. Cited in US v. Ruiz, 136 SCRA 487 (1985.) <BR>Political Offences in \r\nInternational Law. U.P. Law Center, 1977. <BR>International Relations. New Day \r\nPublishers, 1974. <BR></FONT><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" \r\nsize=2>Constitutional Law, Cases and Materials. Central Professional Books, \r\nInc., 1994. <BR>The 1973 Constitution. New Day Publishers, 1973. \r\n<BR><BR></FONT><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>(<I>All \r\nvolumes in this series published by Central Professional Books, Inc., 1999.</I>) \r\n<BR>Constitution Annotated. <BR>Rules of Court Annotated. <BR>Penal Code \r\nAnnotated. <BR>Civil Code Annotated. <BR>Local Government Code Annotated. \r\n<BR>Corporation Code Annotated. <BR>Internal Revenue Code Annotated \r\n<BR><BR><B>Public Administration</B>: <BR>At the Turn of the Century: National \r\nPolicy Issues in the Philippines. Globelink Publications, 1997. <BR>Where Angels \r\nFear to Tread: Politics and Religion. New Day Publishers, 1997. <BR>Cutting \r\nEdge: The Politics of Reform in the Philippines. Woman Today Publications, 1994. \r\n<BR>How to Fight Election Fraud. MOVERS, 1991. <BR>How to Fight Graft. MOVERS, \r\n1991. <BR><BR><B>Literature</B>: <BR>A Frabjous Day and Other Stories. New Day \r\nPublishers, 1997. <BR>Inventing Myself. New Day Publishers, 1994. <BR>The Miriam \r\nDictionary. MOVERS - Youth, 1991. <BR><BR><B>B. PERIODICAL ARTICLES</B>: \r\n<BR><BR>The Visiting Forces Agreement in Constitutional and International \r\nLaw,<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 25 Integrated Bar of the Philippines Law \r\n134 (1999.) <BR>Toward Radical Humanism in a Meta-Technological \r\nSociety,<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Proceedings of the Global Convention \r\non Restoration of Morality and Humanity (1995.) <BR>Philippine Intellectual \r\nProperty Law: A Review in Light of the GATT, 70 Phil. Law Journal 17 (1995.) \r\n<BR>Fighting Philippine Corruption, Proceedings of the Fourth International \r\nAnti-Corruption Conference (1989.) <BR>Some Issues of Immigration Law in a \r\nDeveloping State, 10 Michigan Journal of International Law 251(1989.) <BR>\"CID: \r\nThe Philippine Experiment in Fighting Graft,\" 1 Career Executive Journal 2 \r\n(1989.) <BR>Family Reunification for Refugees: The Philippine Context, 2 \r\nLawyer\'s Review 2 (1988.) <BR>\"Arrest and Search: Guidelines for Policemen,\" 6 \r\nCriminal Justice Journal 32 (1986.) <BR>\"The Supreme Court Applies \'Clear and \r\nPresent Danger:\' But Which One?\" 60 Phil. Law Journal 57 (1985.) <BR>Criminal \r\nProcedure in the Juvenile Justice System, 4 Criminal Justice Journal 31 (1984.) \r\n<BR>The \'New\' Equal Protection, 58 Phil. Law Journal 1 (1983.) <BR>Identifying \r\nthe Political Offender, 56 Phil. Law Journal 395 (1981.) <BR>\"Promotion, \r\nDissemination, and Teaching of International Refugee \r\nLaw:<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Towards a New International Social \r\nOrder,\" 55 Phil. Law Journal 139 (1980) (co-author.) <BR>\"Humanitarian Law in \r\nArmed Conflicts,\" 54 Phil. Law Journal 188 (1979.) <BR>\"Procedural Aspects of \r\nthe Political Offence Doctrine,\" 51 Phil. Law Journal 238 (1976.) <BR>The \r\nArchipelago Concept in the Law of the Sea, 49 Phil. Law Journal 315 (1974.) \r\n<BR><BR><B>MEDIA COVER STORIES</B>: <BR>(Partial List) <BR><BR><B>FOREIGN \r\nMEDIA</B>: <BR><BR>Quotable, Time, 20 July 1992, at p.15. <BR>Showdown: Was the \r\nElection Fair?, Newsweek, 25 May 1992. <BR>Help Wanted, Time, 25 May 1992. \r\n<BR>The Lady and the Star, Asiaweek, 17 May 1992 at p. 38. <BR>People Power II, \r\nTime, 11 May 1992. <BR>Move Over Ross, US News and World Report, 4 May 1992. \r\n<BR>Top Gun, Asiaweek, 4 August 1989. <BR>The Iron Lady of Asia, Asia Magazine, \r\n25 June 1989 at p. 45. <BR>People, Asiaweek, 5 May 1989. <BR>Manila Reformer \r\nAttacks Graft Culture, International Herald Tribune, 27 May 1988 at p.4. \r\n<BR>Fighting the Culture of Corruption Day by Day, New York Times, 26 May 1988. \r\n<BR>Manila\'s Graft Busters Score Some Hard-won Gains, Newsweek, 23 May 1988, at \r\np.13. <BR>Tough Job, Tough Lady, Asiaweek, 1 April 1988, at p.14. <BR>People, \r\nTime, 18 April 1988. <BR><BR><B>LOCAL MEDIA</B>: <BR><BR>Chopping Puno Down, \r\nPhilippine Free Press, 19 June 1999. <BR>Solo: Miriam Santiago, Philippine Star, \r\n23 May 1999. <BR>Battling for Reforms, Philippines Free Press, 28 March 1998. \r\n<BR>The Star Wars Duo, Philippine Graphic, 9 March 1998. <BR>Probing the \r\nPresidentiables: Miriam Defensor Santiago:<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The \r\nCounter Culture Presidential Candidate, Starweek, 14 September 1997. <BR>Sen. \r\nMiriam\'s New Baby, Mirror, 9 September 1997. <BR>In Fighting Form, Philippines \r\nFree Press, 8 March 1997. <BR>Race for Truth, Philippines Free Press, 30 \r\nNovember 1996. <BR>Whom the Gods Wish to Destroy, Philippines Free Press, 27 May \r\n1995. <BR>Miriam Runs Again, Philippines Free Press, 4 March 1995. <BR>Need We \r\nSay More?, National Book Review, February 1994. <BR>The Unsinkable Miriam \r\nSantiago, Sunday Standard, 17 June 1993. <BR>Speaking the Unspeakable in the \r\nSummer of Discontent, Pilipino Reporter, 18 April 1993. <BR>Miriam Magic, \r\nPhilippines Free Press, 23 May 1992.. <BR>The Mind of Miriam, Philippines Free \r\nPress, 25 April 1992. <BR>The Miriam Spirit, Clique, 15 April 1992. <BR>Make \r\nBelieve, Sunday Inquirer Magazine, 8 September 1991. <BR>Miriam The Maverick, \r\nWoman Today, 23 January 1991. <BR>The Frontrunner, Philippine Graphic, 17 \r\nDecember 1990. <BR>Under Fire, Fighting Back, Philippines Free Press, 1 June \r\n1991. <BR>The Unstoppable Miriam D. Santiago, Woman\'s Home Companion, 2 May 1990 \r\nat p.24. <BR>Fists of Fury, Metro, October 1989. <BR>Darling of the Press: Enemy \r\nof the Crooks, Magazine, September 1989 <BR>The Iron Lady Sheds Her Armor, \r\nStarweek, 13 August 1989. <BR>Public Servant of the Year, The Evangelicals \r\nToday, July-August 1989. <BR>Can She Stop Them?, Philippines Free Press, 22 July \r\n1989. <BR>Tapat sa Paglilingkod, Liwayway, 28 November 1988. <BR>Mighty Miriam, \r\nSunday Standard, 16 October 1988, at p.7. <BR>The Soft Side, Sunday Globe, 16 \r\nOctober 1988. <BR>Swimming Against the Tide, Sunday Inquirer, 11 September 1988. \r\n<BR>The Other Lady by the Pasig, Journal Weekender, 28 August 1988, at p.5. \r\n<BR>Platinum Lady, Woman\'s Home Companion, 6 April 1988, at p. 16. <BR>Tiger \r\nLady, National Midweek, 6 April 1988. <BR>The Incorruptible Lady, Philippine \r\nPanorama, 3 April 1988. <BR>Woman of the Hour, Starweek, 12 March 1988. \r\n<BR>Grace Under Pressure, Starweekend, 11 October 1987. <BR><BR><B>BOOK \r\nMENTIONS</B>: <BR><BR>John Naisbitt. Megatrends Asia. Simon &amp; Schuster: New \r\nYork, 1996. (At p. 217). <BR>Luis Teodoro, ed. The Collegian Tradition. \r\nUniversity of the Philippines: Metro Manila, 1996. <BR>James Hamilton-Patterson. \r\nGhosts of Manila. Vintage: London, 1994. (At pp. 104, 109, 257). <BR>Visitacion \r\nde la Torre. The Filipino Child, Images and \r\nInsights.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tower Book House: Metro Manila, \r\n1992. (At p. 264). <BR>James R. Rush. The Ramon Magsaysay Award, Government \r\nService 1988, Miriam Defensor Santiago.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ramon \r\nMagsaysay Award Foundation: Manila, 1988.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \r\n(Pamphlet series by Ramon Magsaysay Center, 1680 Roxas Boulevard, Manila, \r\nPhilippines). <BR>Manuel Duldulao. Images of Manila. Oro Books, Inc.: Metro \r\nManila, 1988. (At p. 104). <BR>Gloria Feliciano, ed. The University of the \r\nPhilippines, A University for Filipinos.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; UP \r\nCommunications Research and Development Foundation: Metro Manila, 1984. (At p. \r\n177). </FONT></P>','Iloilo City','','','',2,20010531112842,'','','Miriam','',8576191,2,7247108,'N',530138,183876,891583,1488543,245499,584337,140704,158683,146429,299372,606498,165202,101213,0,532470,218826,247);
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES (9,'Drilon','Franklin','M',465,'candsenator - franklin drilon.jpg','1945-11-28','','','','','','[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.sendrilon.org.ph/biography.html\">http://www.sendrilon.org.ph/biography.html</A>]<BR><BR>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>BORN on \r\nNovember 28, 1945 in Iloilo City, Franklin M. Drilon is the eldest of four \r\nchildren of Primitiva Drilon and the late Cesar M. Drilon, Sr. A product of the \r\npublic schools, he finished his elementary education in Baluarte Elementary \r\nSchool in Molo, Iloilo City in 1957; high school in UP Iloilo College in 1961, \r\nand received Bachelor of Arts and Bachelor of Laws degrees from the University \r\nof the Philippines (UP) in 1965 and 1969, respectively. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>In UP, he did not \r\nonly excel in academics; he was a student leader. He was elected University \r\nCouncilor of the Student Council; served as associate editor of the Philippine \r\nCollegian, the country’s premier campus paper; member of the Editorial Board of \r\nthe prestigious Philippine Law Journal; member of the Order of the Purple \r\nFeather, the honor society of the U.P. College of Law; and member of the Sigma \r\nRho Fraternity.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>A brilliant legal \r\nmind, he placed third in the 1969 Bar Exams. After passing the Bar Examinations, \r\nhe joined the Sycip, Salazar, Luna, Manalo &amp; Feliciano Law Offices. In 1974, \r\nhe started his career with the Angara, Abello, Concepcion, Regala &amp; Cruz \r\n(ACCRA) Law Offices as senior associate, rose from the ranks to become a \r\npartner, co-managing partner and finally as managing partner and head of the \r\nsaid law firm on August 11, 1986. He resigned in September 1986 leaving the \r\nlucrative practice of law to join the government of President Aquino as Deputy \r\nMinister of Labor.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Drilon served as \r\nSecretary of Labor from January 1987 to January 1990; Secretary of Justice (DOJ) \r\nfrom January 1990 to July 1991; Executive Secretary from July 1991 to June 1992; \r\nagain, Secretary of DOJ from July 1992 to February 1995. He had served in the \r\nCabinet of two Presidents--Corazon Aquino and Fidel V. Ramos. He served in the \r\ngoverning boards and councils of various government corporations and \r\ninstitutions, such as being Chairman of the Philippine National Bank; member of \r\nthe board of Directors of Land Bank and Philippine Airlines; Chairman of the \r\nPresidential Committee on Human Rights and the Cabinet Cluster “E” on Political \r\nand Security matters; Chairman of the Philippine Overseas Employment Agency and \r\nOverseas Worker Welfare Administration; Vice-Chairman, Judicial and Bar \r\nCouncil.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>During the 1995 \r\nSenatorial campaign, Drilon ran on the slogan “Kontra sa Krimen, Justice Agad”, \r\na reminder of how, as Justice Secretary, he spearheaded the crusade to bring to \r\nthe bar of justice the seemingly high and mighty -- the likes of Calauan, Laguna \r\nMayor Antonio Sanchez, Claudio Teehankee, Jr., and Rolito Go. He promised the \r\npeople that, when elected, he will introduce legislation to improve the justice \r\nsystem. The people believed in his cause, and elected him Senator, placing 4th. \r\n</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>He kept his \r\npromise. Thus, immediately after his election as Senator, Drilon filed various \r\nmeasures designed to speed up the trial of cases in the courts, strengthen the \r\nfree legal services to the poor, and declog court dockets by prescribing \r\narbitration rules and procedures on commercial disputes. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>A few months after \r\nthe resumption of the 10th Congress, Senator Drilon was immediately recognized \r\nas one of the foremost legal minds in the Senate when it comes to deliberations \r\nin committee hearings and on the Senate Floor. For his outstanding performance \r\nin his first year in the Senate, Drilon was voted by the Senate press corps as \r\nthe “Most Promising” among the neophyte Senators. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>He did not only \r\nconcentrate on the country’s justice system. He also drafted and filed bills for \r\nthe benefit of the working class; on banking; on housing; on electoral reforms, \r\nto name a few. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>In the 10th \r\nCongress (1995-1998), Senator Drilon was chairman of Senate Committees on \r\nAccountability of Public Officers and Investigations (Blue Ribbon); Banks, \r\nFinancial Institutions and Currencies; Finance Committee Sub-Committee VI and \r\nAgricultural Commission (Agricom) Sub-Committee on Productions and Support \r\nServices. He was vice-chairman of Senate Committee on Justice and Human Rights \r\nand a member of 20 other Senate committees. He was also Member of the powerful \r\nCommission on Appointments. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>In the present 11th \r\nCongress, Drilon serves as the Majority Floor Leader, Chairman of the Committee \r\non Rules and Committee on Accounts, and ex-officio member of all Senate standing \r\ncommittees. He continues to serve as member of the Commission on Appointments. \r\n</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>In professional and \r\ncivic organizations, Drilon was a Bar Examiner on Labor and Social Legislation \r\nin 1979 and 1984; a member of the Makati Rotary Club; past Chapter president of \r\nthe Integrated Bar of the Philippines (IBP); past governor of the Employers \r\nConfederation of the Philippines (ECOP) and past vice-president of the Personnel \r\nManagement Association of the Philippines (PMAP).</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>A former member of \r\nthe National Unification Commission (NUC), Senator Drilon now sits as adviser to \r\nthe government panel in the Government of the Republic of the \r\nPhilippines-National Democratic Front/Communist Party of the Philippines/New \r\nPeople’s Army (GRP-NDF/CPP/NPA) peace talks.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Drilon is a \r\nrecipient of the much coveted award of the Philippine Legion of Honor and a \r\nPresidential citation for outstanding public service. He was named the Most \r\nOutstanding UP Alumnus in government service for 1994 by the UP Law Alumni \r\nAssociation. He was conferred the degree of Doctor of Laws, honoris causa, by \r\nthe Central Philippine University.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>He is also a sports \r\nenthusiast. He jogs a lot to stay physically fit and ready for any challenge \r\nthat he may have to take in some future time. When not reading books, mainly \r\nnon-fiction, or listening to his favorite songs, he tends to the orchid gardens \r\nhis loving wife left behind. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Drilon was married \r\nto the late Atty. Violeta Calvo Drilon, with whom he had two children, Eliza and \r\nPatrick. A widower no more, he recently took a bride, Mila Serrano Genuino, a \r\nsweet and talented lass from Manila and Bicol.</FONT></P>','Molo, Iloilo City','','','',2,20010531112842,'','','Frank','',10880075,1,8518543,'N',784594,194990,1134315,1295402,590033,1253658,353021,119281,127827,274317,396421,56197,187392,0,605606,275654,202);
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES (10,'Enrile','Juan','P',243,'candsenator - enrile.jpg','1924-02-14','','[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.juanponceenrile.com/legislative-achievements.html\">http://www.juanponceenrile.com/legislative-achievements.html</A>]<BR><BR>\r\n<B>JPE - A MAN OF INTEGRITY, COPETENCE AND HONOR</B> <BR><BR>With a political \r\ncareer spanning over three decades, Senator Juan Ponce Enrile is hailed as the \r\nmost veteran and experienced among all the senatorial candidates in the coming \r\nelection. This tax expert from Harvard Law School was first recruited in 1966 to \r\nserve the government as Undersecretary of the Department of Finance. \r\nConcurrently, he held the chairmanship of the Monetary Board and acted as the \r\nInsurance Commissioner and Commissioner of Customs. He went on to occupy more \r\nkey positions in the government including the Department of Justice and \r\nDepartment of National Defense. His seventeen-year stint in the Defense \r\nDepartment was highlighted by his withdrawal of support for the twenty-year old \r\ngovernment of President Ferdinand Marcos, which led to the revolt that triggered \r\nthe historical People Power or EDSA Revolution. <BR><BR>\r\n<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>\r\n<B>FRUITFUL SENATORIAL STINT</B> \r\n<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>\r\nExcellence undoubtedly marked his stay in the government while serving in \r\nvarious capacities. In 1987, he was the lone opposition Senator and thus \r\nprovided a constructive minority by being an effective fiscalizer to the new \r\nAquino government. In 1992, he won a seat in the House of Representatives by a \r\nlandslide representing the First District of Cagayan, his home province. He went \r\nback to the Senate in 1995 and chaired two powerful committees namely, \r\nGovernment Corporations and Public Enterprises, and Ways and Means. <BR><BR>As \r\nChairman of the Senate Committee on Ways and Means, he spearheaded the enactment \r\nof laws, which promote economic reforms by generating more income for the \r\ngovernment. In crafting these legislative measures, he stressed the importance \r\nof a simplified tax system so as not to make taxation more burdensome and \r\nonerous for the taxpaying public as well as promote efficiency in revenue \r\ncollection. To achieve this, he authored the following bills: \r\n<UL>\r\n<LI><B>Republic Act 8424 - Comprehensive Tax Reform Program</B> <BR><BR>SALIENT \r\nFEATURES: \r\n<OL>\r\n<LI>Exemption from tax of all income earned abroad by an Overseas Filipino \r\nWorker thus enabling the OFWs to save a substantial amount of their hard-earned \r\nincome for their families. \r\n<LI>Exemption from capital gains tax of proceeds realized from the sale of one\'s \r\nfamily home provided that said proceeds will utilized to acquire another \r\nresidential home. \r\n<LI>Substantial increase in personal exemption granted to individual taxpayers \r\nearning compensation income. \r\n<LI>Substantial increase in personal allowances granted to dependents of \r\nindividual taxpayers. </LI></OL><BR>\r\n<LI><B>SBN 2048 - An Act Exempting from Tax Certain Allowances and Benefits \r\nGranted to Members of the Armed Forces of the Philippines (AFP)</B><BR><BR>\r\n<LI><B>SBN 2082 - An Act Exempting from Tax All Allowances and Benefits Granted \r\nto Public School Teachers</B><BR><BR>\r\n<LI><B>RA 8751 - An Act Providing Rules for Countervailing Duties on the \r\nImportation of Subsidized Products.</B> It has for its purpose the protection of \r\nlocal industries, which will be adversely affected by a massive importation of \r\nsubsidized products.<BR><BR>\r\n<LI><B>RA 8752 - An Act Providing the Rules for the Imposition of Anti-Dumping \r\nDuty.</B> Its purpose is to shield the local producers from the harsh effects of \r\nimportation of cheap dumped goods.<BR><BR>\r\n<LI><B>RA 8800 - An Act Providing Safeguards for Agricultural Products whose \r\nQuantitative Restrictions had been Replaced with Ordinary Customs Duties.</B> \r\nThis bill seeks to protect the agricultural sector from the flooding of low \r\nquality products imported from abroad.<BR><BR>\r\n<LI><B>SBN 2232 - An Act Elevating the Rank of the Court of Tax Appeals (CTA) to \r\nthe level of a Collegiate Court with Special Jurisdiction.</B> This bill will \r\nenlarge the jurisdiction of the CTA and its organizational structure to promote \r\nefficient tax collection.<BR><BR>\r\n<LI><B>SBN 2208 - An Act Providing Optimum Performance in Revenue Collection \r\nthrough Lateral Attrition.</B> This bill grants special incentives and rewards \r\nfor exemplary service in revenue-generating agencies of the government. It \r\nlikewise imposes a penalty to employees of said agencies who fail to meet the \r\ncollection quota.<BR><BR></LI></UL>As Chairman of the Senate Committee on \r\nGovernment Corporations and Public Enterprises, he has exposed certain \r\nirregularities in the government, which led to a string of graft charges against \r\nthe culprit involved. Incisive legislative inquiries and well-documented public \r\nhearings were concluded in order to shed light on the following controversial \r\nissues: PEA-Amari Land Scam, Tax Credit Scam in the DOF and Purchase of Luxury \r\nVehicles by DECS Officials. <BR><BR>\r\n<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>\r\n<B>AS A SENATOR-JUDGE</B> \r\n<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>\r\nHis fruitful stint in the Senate was marked with a genuine desire to serve the \r\npublic. This was again proven during the much-publicized impeachment trial of \r\nPresident Joseph Ejercito Estrada. As one of the Senator-Judges, the public \r\nmarveled at Senator Enrile\'s admirable display of legal expertise. As a lawyer \r\nwho has not lost a single case when he practiced law after passing the bar with \r\na perfect score in Commercial Law, he dutifully performed the gargantuan task of \r\nrendering impartial justice during the impeachment trial. His strong \r\ndetermination to uphold the Constitution earned him the sternest of rebuke from \r\nsome sectors that misunderstood the sincerity of his stand. <BR><BR>Every inch a \r\nseasoned statesman, Senator Enrile managed to regain the confidence of the \r\npeople when they realized the candor and honesty of his intentions. In the \r\nrecent SWS Survey, he landed in the magic 12, a feat that was elusive even to \r\nthose who figured prominently during the impeachment trial by joining the \r\nbandwagon. <BR><BR>This coming election, the public will again bear witness to \r\nan active demonstration of how democracy operates in the country by putting in \r\npower to only those candidates with proven competence, integrity and genuine \r\ndesire to serve the Filipino people. One such man is SENATOR JUAN PONCE ENRILE, \r\nwho stood up not only like a man, but also as an honorable statesman. <BR>','','','','[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.juanponceenrile.com/profile-english.html\">http://www.juanponceenrile.com/profile-english.html</A>]<BR><BR>\r\n<P>\r\nOne such man grew up poor and out of wedlock and continues to influence world \r\nevents. His EDSA led revolt became a model for toppling repressive regimes all \r\nover the world. <BR><BR>Juan Ponce Enrile was born on Valentine\'s Day in a \r\nremote village in Cagayan. He was christened Juanito Furagganan, taking his \r\nmother\'s name. <BR><BR>Looking for better opportunities, the young Juanito left \r\nGonzaga, Cagayan for the poblacion and enrolled in school by working as a \r\nservant to his mother\'s relative. <BR><BR>He later transferred to Aparri and \r\nenrolled at the Cagayan Valley Institute. <BR><BR>World War II broke out and \r\nJuanito, now a young man joined the guerillas. He was caught, imprisoned and \r\ntortured. He escaped, and at the end of the war, was serving in the U.S. \r\nQuartermaster depot in Aparri, Cagayan. <BR><BR>While the war was raging, his \r\nhalf sisters evacuated to Aparri and learned about Juanito. <BR><BR>After the \r\nwar, Juanito met his father in the latter\'s Law Office in Binondo, Manila. \r\n<BR><BR>Don Alfonso brought Juanito home to Malabon. He was given a new name, \r\nJuan Ponce Enrile. He resumed his High School education at the St. James Academy \r\nin Malabon. <BR><BR>In 1947, he entered Ateneo de Manila graduating cum laude \r\nwith an Associate in Arts Degree. In the UP, he graduated cum laude and \r\nsalutatorian of UP Law Class 1953. He later passed the Bar Examinations placing \r\n11th with a 91.72% rating and getting a perfect score in commercial law. \r\n<BR><BR>He was offered a scholarship by the Harvard University where he earned a \r\nMaster of Laws degree specializing in taxation and corporate reorganization. \r\n<BR><BR>Returning to the Philippines, he joined the Ponce Enrile, Siguion Reyna, \r\nMontecillo, Bello Law Office where he emerged as a top corporate and litigation \r\nlawyer. He never lost a case. <BR><BR>In 1966, he was appointed as \r\nUndersecretary of Finance, acting Insurance Commissioner of Customs and acting \r\nChairman of the Monetary Board. In 1968-70 he served as Secretary of Justice. He \r\nwas appointed Secretary of National Defense in 1970, a position he held for \r\nalmost seventeen (17) years until 1986. <BR><BR>He became an Assemblyman of \r\nCagayan in 1978 and was reelected in 1984. <BR><BR>The events of February 1986 \r\nmarked turning point in the history of the Philippines and in Enrile\'s career. \r\nFollowing the turbulent snap elections of February 7,1986, and amid the \r\nprolonged crisis that gripped the country after the assassination of former \r\nSenator Benigno Aquino, Jr., Enrile withdrew his support for the Marcos \r\ngovernment and led the revolt that triggered what would be known as the People \r\nPower or EDSA Revolution. <BR><BR>Together with a handful of officers and men, \r\nhe rallied the ranks of the Philippine military behind the rebellion, which \r\nculminated in the fall of the Marcos government. <BR><BR>It was during this time \r\nthat hundreds of thousands of citizens poured into EDSA (Epifanio Delos Santos \r\nAvenue) and for four days surrounded the camp where Enrile and his men were \r\nholding out, thus averting a bloody confrontation between the rebels and Marcos \r\nloyalist group in the military. <BR><BR>Mrs. Corazon Aquino, who was proclaimed \r\nthe New President, reappointed Enrile as Secretary of National Defense. He the \r\npost after six months, however, as differences over policy with the new \r\nadministration grew. <BR><BR>In 1987, he ran and won as opposition Senator. \r\nSubsequently, was the lone opposition Senator in the Senate. As Minority Floor \r\nLeader, he was a member of all the standing committees of the Senate. He was \r\nalso a member of the Senate Electoral Tribunal and the Commission on \r\nAppointments. <BR><BR>In the May 11, 1992 elections, he won a seat in the House \r\nof Representatives by a landslide representing the First District of Cagayan, \r\nhis home province. He joined the Liberal Party, to which his father belonged, \r\nshortly after. <BR><BR>In the May 1995 elections he ran and won a seat once \r\nagain in the Senate under the Lakas Coalition. Again he was a member of the \r\nCommission on Appointments and Chairman of the Senate Ways and Means Committee \r\nand the Committee on Government Corporations and Public Enterprises. <BR><BR>At \r\nthat time, he authored the Comprehensive Tax Reform Program, which eventually \r\nbecame Republic Act 8424. Among the inclusions that would greatly benefit the \r\nOverseas Filipino Worker in this law is the exemption of their income earned \r\nabroad from taxation, thus enabling them to save a more substantial amount from \r\ntheir salaries for their families. In addition to this, is the exemption from \r\ncapital gains tax, proceeds realized from the sale of one\'s family home provided \r\nthat such gains would be utilized to acquire another residential home. \r\n<BR><BR>During the 10th and 11th Congress, Senator Juan Ponce Enrile filed \r\nseveral legislative landmarks namely: the; SB No. 2068 which seeks to increase \r\nby at least 100% the personal and additional tax exemptions granted to \r\nindividual income tax payers; SB. No. 2089 which seeks to reduce the income tax \r\nrates on taxable income; SB 1887 which would allow the deductibility from \r\ntaxable income of interest payments on housing loans, and in addition, SB No. \r\n2082 which seeks to exempt all the allowances and benefits granted to public \r\nschool teachers, including those in state colleges and universities from income \r\ntax. <BR><BR>He has gone on to serve as one of the most productive and \r\noutstanding senators in the present Congress. <BR><BR>He has continued to serve \r\nas he has lived- with excellence, determination and desire to serve the Filipino \r\npeople. <BR>','Gonzaga, Cagayan','','','',2,20010531112842,'','[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.juanponceenrile.com/legislative-agenda.html\">http://www.juanponceenrile.com/legislative-agenda.html</A>]<BR><BR>\r\n<P>\r\nI consider the following as the top priorities for the nation included in my \r\nlegislative agenda as Senator of the Philippines should I be fortunate enough to \r\nbe re-elected as Senator this coming elections: <BR><BR><B>THE ECONOMY</B> \r\n<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>\r\nWe have to calibrate carefully the exchange rate so that we neither price \r\nourselves out of the world market nor allow the peso to depreciate. An \r\nacceptable exchange rate must be determined in relation to our neighbors and our \r\ncompetitors. With respect to interest rates, I advocate the policy of fostering \r\ncompetition - not regulation - to bring down interest rate levels. I will \r\ndirectly compete with the commercial banks by providing credit lower rates. \r\n<BR><BR>I have long ago taken the position that we must reduce the tax burden on \r\nthe people. Primarily, I am advocating this as a creative way of increasing the \r\nfree or disposable income of taxpayers and spurring economic activity. \r\n<BR><BR>We must realize that no matter how much we press for salary increases, \r\nemployers are hardly in a position, especially given the economic situation, to \r\ngive their employees the substantial wage increase they need to cope with the \r\nrise in cost of living. A cut in taxes will automatically increase the take home \r\npay of our salaried employees and thus enable them to buy more goods. The \r\neconomy will benefit in turn from increased spending and economic activity. \r\n<BR><BR>During the last Congress, I filed two related bills aimed at achieving \r\nthis goal to wit, Senate Bill No. 2068 which seeks to increase the allowable \r\npersonal and addition exemptions of individual taxpayers by at least 100%; and \r\nSenate Bill No. 2089 aimed at reducing the corresponding tax rates of individual \r\ntaxpayers by at least 50%. Public hearings for the passage of this bill were \r\nheld and the corresponding Committee Reports were prepared. I even went to the \r\nextent of sponsoring it in the Senate before we adjourned. <BR><BR>Moreover, to \r\nfurther protect the consuming public from the predatory practices of some \r\nunscrupulous businessmen, I will pursue the enactment of an Anti-Trust Law that \r\nwill check and penalize any act or practice that will in one way or the other \r\nresult in any combination or monopoly in restraint of trade. <BR><BR>If \r\nre-elected, I vow to pursue these and other measures aimed at reducing the tax \r\nburden on the people so that they can have more money in their hands for their \r\nbasic needs. <BR><BR><B>PEACE AND ORDER</B> \r\n<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>\r\nI advocate the return of jurisdiction and control over the police to the local \r\ngovernments. Nationalizing the police has only turned the law enforcement effort \r\ninto a bureaucratic mess. We should maintain a national constabulary at a \r\nnational level to attend to peace and order problems that are national in \r\nnature. <BR><BR><B>GOVERNMENT REORGANIZATION</B> \r\n<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>\r\nI advocate the following: \r\n<UL>\r\n<LI>Adoption of the generalized civil service system of the British Civil \r\nService, in lieu of our present compartmentalized system. Under that system, a \r\ncivil servant is considered as an employee of the entire government service not \r\nof specific departments or agencies. Thus, he or she can be easily moved from \r\none department to another. \r\n<LI>Review of the entire government bureau so as to remove duplication of \r\nagencies and services to make the government not only less wasteful but more \r\nefficient as well. \r\n<LI>Restoration of the full powers of the Commission on Appointments of Congress \r\nunder which all officials of the bureaucracy down to assistant director level \r\nmust pass the scrutiny of the Commission. This will help arrest profusion of \r\npolitical appointments to the civil service. \r\n<LI>Abolition of the Judicial and Bar Council, which at present recommends to \r\nthe President appointments to the courts. </LI></UL><B>EDUCATION</B> \r\n<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>\r\nTo achieve high-quality education, we should focus attention on the three areas \r\nwhere reform can result in positive change for our society: \r\n<UL>\r\n<LI>The quality of teachers and teacher training; \r\n<LI>The physical facilities of our institutions of learning; and \r\n<LI>The substance of the curriculum. </LI></UL>During the past Congress, I filed \r\nseveral Senate Bills that will boost our education system into the new \r\nmillennium. An example of which concentrates on information technology (IT) \r\neducation since the IT industry is the wave of the future. Another bill proposes \r\nto exempt the allowances granted to public school teachers from taxation to \r\nentice more people to join the academe. <BR><BR>We must also create more State \r\nColleges and Universities so that more Filipino students may be given the \r\nopportunity to enroll at a low cost. <BR><BR>If re-elected, I shall continue to \r\npursue my vision for Education by re-filing these bills, file other related \r\nmeasures and work on the passage of the same. <BR><BR><B>NATIONAL SECURITY</B> \r\n<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>\r\nI wholly support the modernization of our armed forces. What we need are modern \r\nweapon systems. Because we do not have all the available resources for full AFP \r\nmodernization, we should set priorities. Between the Navy and the Air Force, I \r\nbelieve we should pour resources into the Navy because we are an archipelagic \r\nnation. <BR><BR><B>FOREIGN RELATIONS</B> \r\n<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>\r\nWe should nurture our membership in ASEAN and other Asian forums; APEC and our \r\nrelations with countries like the United States of America, Canada, Australia \r\nand Latin America. Our ties with Europe and the Middle East are of vital \r\nimportance as well particularly in terms of trade and investment. We must strive \r\nto contribute our share to the work of the United Nations, of which the \r\nPhilippines is a founding member. <BR><BR><B>CONSTITUTIONAL REFORM</B> \r\n<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>\r\nI believe we should face, once and for all, the challenge of amending our \r\nConstitution. Among the reforms that I consider urgent are the following: \r\n<UL>\r\n<LI>The desynchronization of elections; \r\n<LI>The election of senators by regions; \r\n<LI>The review of the terms of office of all elective officials of the \r\ngovernment; \r\n<LI>The return of supervision and control of the police to the local \r\ngovernments; \r\n<LI>The restoration of the full powers of the Commission on Appointments to \r\nreview presidential appointments; \r\n<LI>The transfer of court supervision from the Supreme Court to the Department \r\nof Justice as provided for in the 1935 Constitution; \r\n<LI>The creation of a two-party system; and \r\n<LI>The re-examination of the constitutional provisions governing the economy \r\nand private ownership. </LI></UL>','JPE','',9237333,2,7212000,'N',584571,312404,820178,1472156,279188,438280,148348,169572,143883,320732,606902,148062,134162,0,515709,235247,321);
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES (11,'Ejercito Estrada','Luisa Ejercito','P',465,'candsenator - loi ejercito.jpg','1930-06-02','','','<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Being a doctor of medicine \r\nherself, Dr. Loi Ejercito Estrada has put health on th top shelf of her program \r\nfor the people. She relies on the statistics that thousands if not a million of \r\nthe poor especially live and die without seeing a doctor. So the solution is \r\nmore clinics and hospitals, desirably one for each town with the doctors and \r\nnurses and personnel subsidized by more taxes. And no one should be denied \r\nassistance or should be banned and even kept imprisoned in a hospital if he \r\ncannot pay for such service.<BR><BR>This goes in tandem with a huge program for \r\neducation where the poor are given enough chances to move up to a better life. \r\nThere should be more scholarships offered and they should put a complete stop to \r\n\"colorum\" schools. There should be more schools, but these should be keenly \r\nsupervised. There must be more teachers even if we have to pay them topnotch \r\nsalaries. Only then can we hope for the children to grow up to our \r\ntargets.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Labor is needing much \r\nimprovement. More jobs should be generated and that means more companies should \r\nbe encouraged in putting up shop and employ as many as they can pay decently. \r\nBut we must be exceedingly sure that the businesses don\'t fold up because of \r\nunreasonable demands of labor, such as sky-high wages. We must make sure too \r\nthat proper taxes are paid, both by employers and employed to keep the \r\ngovernment on a steady keel. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Security is not too much of \r\na problem if it is only a danger of outside interference we are looking at. The \r\nproblem is within us, among us and because of us. We are still in a state of \r\nrebellion from the communists and the Muslim brothers. They have to be educated \r\nto join the civil society and not mess around with us. While the police and \r\nmilitary should always maintain a close watch, the civil government and civilian \r\ninstitutions can do a lot to alleviate their grievances and poor station in \r\nlife.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>This is the root of the \r\nproblem of poverty - Lack of work, especially quality work that can sustain the \r\nlives of people all around. This demands their employment and education to \r\nuplift themselves. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>There are too many of us \r\nstill living in hovels and eating only twice a day and only ride wiith, \r\nprobably, a little \"bagoong.\" There must be a remedy to that and the remedy is \r\nwork and education.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>When all is said and done, \r\nwe have to go back to one who said laws must be fashioned out more for the poor \r\nthat fore the rich. <BR></FONT></P>','','','','Iba, Zambales','','','',2,20010531112842,'','','Loi','',9393155,2,7834231,'N',579134,211452,997379,1652645,308730,459490,138096,203312,169921,375124,680773,179023,115870,0,546845,249701,230);
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES (12,'Flavier','Juan','M',233,'candsenator - juan flavier.jpg','1935-06-23','','','','','','[Source: <A HREF=\"http://ebantay.free3.org/candidate.php3?c=9\">http://ebantay.free3.org/candidate.php3?c=9</A>]<BR><BR>\r\n<P>\r\nDr. Flavier is a Senator of the Republic of the Philippines. He is Chairman of the Social Justice, Welfare and Development Committee of the Senate. He also sat on the Cultural Communities Committee and the Science and Technology Committee. \r\n<P>\r\nFrom 1992 until 1995, he was a Cabinet Member, serving as Secretary of Health. In 1977, he served as President of the Philippine Rural Reconstruction Movement. He was also President of the International Institute of Rural Reconstruction from 1978 until 1992. Dr. Flavier received his medical credentials from the University of the Philippines in 1960. He received a Masters in Public Health from Johns Hopkins University in 1969.','Tondo, Manila','','','',2,20010531112842,'','','Johnny F.','',11276684,1,8877404,'N',838110,193365,1272476,1471982,535334,917700,330654,121774,125439,261215,408749,65874,227148,0,734888,281205,300);
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES (13,'Herrera','Ernesto','F',233,'candsenator - ernesto herrera.jpg','1942-09-11','','','','','','[Source: <A HREF=\"http://ebantay.free3.org/candidate.php3?c=23\">http://ebantay.free3.org/candidate.php3?c=23</A>]<BR><BR>\r\n<FONT face=\"helvetica, arial\" size=2>\r\n<P>Former Senator Ernesto \"Boy\" Herrera earned for himself an enviable \r\nreputation as a trade union leader, an advocate of law and order, a crusader \r\nagainst drug abuse, an expert on public finance an done of the outstanding \r\nsenators of the 8th, 9th and 10th Congresses. \r\n<P>He earned his LI.B from the University of the Visayas in 1966. In 1995, he \r\ntook his Masters Degree (summa cum laude) in Public Administration, major in \r\nPublic Finance, at the Lyceum of the Philippines, where he also obtained his \r\nPh.D (magna cum laude) in Fiscal Studies in 1998. The thesis for his M.A. was a \r\ncomparative analysis of the tax systems of the ASEAN countries and Hong Kong. \r\nHis Ph.D. dissertation was o the issues and problems of legislative control of \r\nthe national budget. He was cconferred honorary doctorates in humanities by the \r\nUniversity of the Visayas in 1994 and by the University of Bohol in 1998. \r\n<P>Boy Herrera spent most of his professional life in the cause of labor, mainly \r\nas General Secretary of the Trade Union Congress of the Philippines. \r\n<P>He was the only Filipino member of the Executive Board of the International \r\nConfederation of Free Trade Unions iin Brussels, Belgium, from 1988 - 1992; a \r\nconsultant on employment and workers\' education of the International Labour \r\nOrganisation (ILO) in Geneva, Switzerland. He headed the Workers\' Delegation to \r\nthe 75th Session of the ILO where he delivered a major address on human rights. \r\n<P>He is the first Asian, and only the second individual, to recieve the George \r\nMeanly International Human Rights Award in 1985. The first individual awardee \r\nwas Lech Walesa of the Solidarity Movement, former President of Poland. He was \r\nlikewise conferred the International Award of Honor by the International \r\nNarcotics Enforcement Officers Association in New York, U.S.A., in 1991. \r\n<P>Here at home, Boy Herrera was the workers\' representative in the National \r\nWages Council, the Social Security Commission and the National Manpower and \r\nYouth Council. He is the Founding Chairman of teh Citizens\' DrugWatch \r\nFoundation, Inc. and President of both the Carlos P. Garcia Foundatin, Inc. and \r\nthe University of the Visayas Alumni Association. In recognition of his crusade \r\nagainst drugs particularly to protect the youth from its perricious effects, \r\nHerrera received the 1992 Gintong Ama ng Bayan Award, the highest award given by \r\nthe Gintong Ama/Ina Foundation of the Philippines. \r\n<P>Boy Herrera rose to national prominence as a member of the Agrava \r\nFact-Finding Board that investigated the assassination of Benigno S. Aquino Jr. \r\n<P>Herrera was first elected to the Senate in 1987. In the national elections of \r\n1992, he won his seecond Senate term, ranking second among the re-electionist \r\nsenators. In the Senate, he chaired the Committees on Ways and Means, Finance, \r\nPublic Services, Labor, Tourism and Illegal Drugs. He wa a member of the \r\nCommission of Appointments, chairman of its committee on Constitutional Offices. \r\n\r\n<P>He was a member of the Congressional Commissions on Education (Edcom, 1990) \r\nthat reviewed and assessed the Philippine educational system and on Health \r\n(1992). In the Edcom, he was responsible for landmark reforms in vocational \r\neducation and training that resulted in the establishment of the Technical \r\nEducational and Skills Development Authority (TESDA). He also sat on the \r\nExecutive-Legislative National Water Crisis Commission. He was a member of the \r\nCongressional Commission on Health and was responsible for the Philippine Health \r\nInsurance System. \r\n<P>In the Senate, his legislative record was strong on labor, employment, \r\nfiscal, education and law and order policies, and was its leading advocate in \r\nthe control and prevention of drug abuse. \r\n<P>In the Commission on Appointment, he chaired the committees on Accounts, \r\nConstitutional Bodies and Sciece &amp; Technology. He is also a member of the \r\nCongressional Commission on Labor. \r\n<P>He has 34 laws to his credit, one of the highest achivements in the 8th, 9th, \r\n10th and the on-going, 11th, Congresses. \r\n<P>Herrera was one of the three complainants that became the basis of the \r\nArticles of Impeachment against Joseph E. Estrada. He was a moving force of the \r\nPower Power II. \r\n<P>Born in Samboan, Cebu, on September 11, 1942, he is married to Lourdes Cuico \r\nof Cebu City and has four children: Luzil, June, Ernesto II and Ernesto III. \r\nErnesto F. Herrera, like Apolinario Mabini, overcame his physical handicap \r\n(cause by polio during his childhood) to become one of the country\'s outstanding \r\nlearders. \r\n<P>Making a crippled country whole again \r\n<P><I>Ako po\'y si Boy Herrera - tubong Cebu - anak ng isang sundalo. Ang aking \r\nnanay ay Boholana. \r\n<P>Di man n\'yo naitatanong - ako\'y nagkasakit ng polio noong ako\'y apat na taong \r\ngulang lamang. \r\n<P>Sa kabila ng aming kahirapan at nang aking kapansanan - ako po\'y nakatapos ng \r\nabogasya sa University of the Visayas. \r\n<P>Matapos akong magturo sumandali, ako\'y naging organizer ng mga estibidor sa \r\nCebu at ng mga trabahador sa malaking pataniman sa Mindanao. \r\n<P>Nilibot ko ang mga asyendang pinya ng Dole at Del Monte - kadalasan angkas sa \r\nmotorsiklo - at (kung minamalas naman) sa bubong ng jeepney. \r\n<P>Ako ang isa sa mga nagtatag ng TUCP at ako ay naging Secretary General nito. \r\n<P></I>Then Senator Benigno Aquino was assassinated - and I became a member of \r\nthe Agrava Fact-Finding Board. Only then did I realize how much harm an \r\noppressive Government can do to a nation and its people. \r\n<P><I>Kung walang pangitain - walang kakayahan - at walang moralidad ang mga \r\nnasa poder, sila\'y nagsisilbing hagupit sa taong-bayan. \r\n<P>Nilabanan ko ang nais ni Maros na pawalang sala ang mga sundalong pumaslang \r\nkay Ninoy. Ito ang nagbunsod ng EDSA I. \r\n<P>Ako\'y hinirang ni Presidente Cory upang kumandidato para sa Senado noong \r\n1987. \r\n<P></I>During my first term, I realized that being a Senator required advanced \r\nand continuing education. So, without neglecting my duties as Senator, I went to \r\nnight school. I took my master\'s degree in public finance graduating summa cum \r\nlaude. I enrolled for a doctorate in fiscal studies, graduating magna cum laude. \r\n\r\n<P>During my two terms as Senator - from 1987 until 1999 - I authored 34 \r\nlandmark laws. I wrote the TESDA Law to prepare young people for jobs. I wrote \r\nthe Migrant Workers Act to protect OFWs. I wrote the Death Penalty Law to stop \r\nheinous crimes. \r\n<P>I passed the Paternity Leave Act to strengthen the family. A strong family, \r\nas a I found early in life, is an indispensable support to a strong nation. And \r\ni founded the Citizens\' DrugWatch to fight drug addiction. My other laws are on \r\nmonetary and fiscal policies and on public health. \r\n<P>Laws I now would like to write - if i am reelected to the Senate - are those \r\nthat will create jobs and ensure that our society is free of corruption. \r\n<P><I>Napakarami sa ating mga Pilipino ang nilulumpo ng karalitaan at \r\nkamangmangan. Mistulang mga pipi ang ating mga manggagawa - sapagkat di nila \r\nmaipaabot sa mga nasa kapangyarihan ang kanilang mga inaasam-asam. At napakarami \r\nsa ating mga pinuno - bulag na sa salapi - ay bingi pa rin sa himutok ng \r\nkanilang mga nasasakop. \r\n<P></I>These past three years, ang buong bansa natin ay nasalanta ng katiwalian. \r\nLike the polio virus, corruption entered the nation\'s bloodstream - and if left \r\nunchecked, maaring masalanta ang buong bansa. \r\n<P>This was why I joined Heherson Alvarez and Mike Defensor in making the \r\naccusations na naging basihan ng mga Articles of Impeachment against President \r\nEstrada. \r\n<P>EDSA II launched this People Power Coalition with a clear purpose. \r\n<P>Never again should we put in power the minions of a corrupt administration. \r\n<P>Never again should we stand by and watch powerful people prevent Filipinos \r\nfrom walking tall and proud in the global community. \r\n<P>This - my beloved countrymen - is the parable of my life that I offer to you. \r\nTogether, let us do great things for our country and our people.</P></FONT>','Samboan, Cebu','','','',2,20010531112842,'','','Boy','',6504566,1,5186007,'N',387174,79504,701331,684222,257457,539271,332303,73463,128826,231198,263865,32550,96141,0,382685,199259,142);
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES (14,'Honasan','Gregorio','B',465,'candsenator - gringo honasan.jpg','1948-03-14','','','<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>The legislative agenda of \r\nSenator Honasan for the 11th Congress revolves around Good Government and \r\nEfficient Bureaucracy; Reforms in AFP and PNP; Industrialization and Genuine \r\nEconomic Development; Natural Resources and Environmental Protection and \r\nManagement; Good Education for all and Opportunities for the Marginalized \r\nSectors. His legislative priorities include:</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>The Land Use Act (Senate \r\nBill No. 660)</B> - an act providing for the national land use policy and \r\nplanning network expected to provide a systematic zoning of land resources for \r\nindustrial, economic, agricultural and community use.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>Clean Water Act (Senate \r\nBill 1710)</B> - an act providing for a comprehensive water resource policy and \r\nwater sector development, creating the Water Resources Management commission and \r\nfor other purposes;</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>An Act Declaring a \r\nNational Peace Policy (Senate Bill 660) </B>- creating the Commission on Peace \r\nand provide the guideline for government\'s dealings with rebels, insurgents and \r\nsecessionist groups; </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>Reorganization Act of the \r\nDAR (Senate Bill 1589)</B> - includes the creation of the Department of Agrarian \r\nReform Adjudication Board or DARAB; and</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>Magna Carta for PNP \r\n(Senate Bill no. 1918)</B> - seen as the answer to the woes of policemen over \r\nlow pay, \"palakasan system,\" security of tenure, financial assistance and \r\nbenefits, logistical problems and training</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>Amending the AFP \r\nRetirement Law (Senate Bill 1312)</B> - The bill seeks to correct the injustice \r\ncommitted against men in uniform over the computation of their retirement \r\nbenefits</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Full Implementation of \r\nIndigenous People\'s Right Act or IPRA - to give cultural minorities due \r\nprotection </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>PERA for Government \r\nWorkers (Senate Bill 1444)</B> - provides a P1,000 Personal Economic Relief \r\nAssistance (PERA) to government workers <BR></FONT></P>','','','','Baguio City','','','',2,20010531112842,'','','Gringo','',9970815,2,7750473,'N',639176,248040,888214,1627528,356937,464572,153491,211669,164807,353634,661099,177687,140447,0,540702,231298,338);
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES (15,'Lacson','Panfilo','M',243,'candsenator - ping lacson.jpg','1948-06-01','','','[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.pinglacson.net/ping_lacson_ie/platform.htm\">http://www.pinglacson.net/ping_lacson_ie/platform.htm</A>]<BR><BR>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>1.) PEACE AND \r\nORDER</B></FONT></P>\r\n<P><B><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>2.) ANTI-GRAFT \r\nAND CORRUPTION</FONT></B></P>\r\n<P><B><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>3.) GOOD \r\nGOVERNANCE</FONT></B></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>\"MISSION POSSIBLE\" \r\nSA SENADO</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>UPANG SUGPUIN ANG \r\nKRIMEN AT KURAKOT</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>1.) Magtatag ng \r\nisang \"Independent Commision Against Corruption\" na hindi saklaw ninuman. Maski \r\nng Pangulo ng Pilipinas upang makasigurong anumang imbestigasyon nito laban sa \r\nkatiwalian ay di maimpluwensiyahan ninuman.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>2.) Magsabatas ng \r\nisang sistema nang pagmomonitor ng pananalapi para masugpo ang \"Unexplained \r\nWealth.\"</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>3.) Palakasin pa \r\nang mga batas laban sa mga sindikato ng krimen, lalong-lalo na sa droga, \r\nkidnap-for-ransom at iba pang malaking krimen.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>4.) Maiangat ang \r\nkabuhayan ng ating kapulisan at militar upang higit silang maging epektibo sa \r\nkanilang panunungkulan.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>PROTEKSIYON SA \r\nMAMIMILI AT MALILIIT NA MAGANGALAKAL</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>1.) Palakasin ang \r\nConsumer Code upang bigyang proteksiyon ang mamimili laban sa masama at \r\nmapang-abusong serbisyo ng ng mga public utility vehicles tulad ng mga cellphone \r\ncompanies, bulok na mga barko, transportasyon atbp.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>2.) Itaguyod ang \r\nkapayakan ng mga maliliit na negosyante laban sa sobrang buwis at mapaniil na \r\nregulasyon.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>3.) Gawing simple \r\nat taxpayer-friendly ang sistema ng buwis, upang maiwasan ang kurakot at \r\nmadagdagan ang kita ng pamahalaan.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>4.) Maitaguyod ang \r\npagkakaroon ng small at medium enterprises upang magkaroon ng dagdag na \r\nikabubuhay ng mga ordinaryo nating mamamayan at maiangat aang kanilang \r\nkabuhayan.</FONT></P>','','','[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.pinglacson.net/ping_netscape/profile_content.htm\">http://www.pinglacson.net/ping_netscape/profile_content.htm</A>]<BR><BR>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 size=2>With \r\nLacson again in anti-crime mode, kidnappings and bank robberies have dropped \r\ndramatically. Also, he has retrieved some 448 carnapped or missing vehicles \r\nbeing used by police officers; relieved from duty 42 police officers, including \r\nfour generals and two colonels, who headed major Manila police commands; banned \r\nofficers from playing golf during office hours at the PNP\'s sprawling Camp Crame \r\nheadquarters in suburban Quezon City; and stopped the police checkpoints on \r\ndelivery vans bringing vegetables, fish and other supplies to Manila from the \r\nprovinces. These unpopular checkpoints tend to jack up the price of prime goods \r\nin the capital because businessmen pass on the cost of extortion money to \r\nconsumers.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#333333 \r\nsize=2>Lacson has fielded plainclothes cops to monitor the activities of \r\nextorting policemen.To hardened scalawags in uniform, Lacson vows, in rather \r\ndramatic language:</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 \r\nsize=2>Policemen are now suddenly courteous. Bad cops have turned good. \r\n</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 size=2>Not \r\nsurprisingly, a lot of rank-and-file police don\'t like Lacson. \"The moment I \r\naccepted the command,\" he says, \"I knew my life would become miserable. I would \r\nlose a lot of friends even as I created new enemies. Those I fight, I do not \r\nhate. Those I protect, I do not love. It is simply a matter of duty.\" Even if \r\nnot everyone agrees how that duty should be discharged. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 \r\nsize=2>Before assuming the top PNP post, Lacson served as chief of the PAOCTF. \r\nLacson joined the now defunct Philippine Constabulary upon graduation from the \r\nPhilippine Military Academy in 1971.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 size=2>He \r\nserved most of his junior years with the Metrocom Intelligence and Security \r\nGroup (MISG) from 1971 to 1976. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 size=2>At \r\nthe height of the communist insurgency in Northern Luzon, he was PC/INP \r\nProvincial Commander of Isabela from 1988 to 1989 after which he was reassigned \r\nas commander of the Cebu Metrodiscom until 1992.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 size=2>His \r\nnext assignment brought him back to Luzon as provincial director of Laguna in \r\n1992. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 \r\nsize=2>Lacson\'s colorful career as crimebuster peaked when he was appointed \r\nchief of the Presidential Anti-Crime Commission (PACC}.</FONT></P>','Imus, Cavite','','','',2,20010531112842,'','','Ping Lacson','',10190565,2,7867813,'N',608116,224970,950764,1669181,332444,433882,184359,193558,153071,327115,667210,176262,141033,0,571762,253986,268);
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES (16,'Lozano','Oliver','O',249,'candsenator - oliver lozano.jpg','1940-05-13','','','<FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>1. Work for the release of $ \r\n647 million Marcos deposit with PNB to be shared with the entire Filipino people \r\nregardless of religious and political beliefs in accordance with the last will \r\nof President Ferdinand E. Marcos. Hindi pera bawat isa, kundi pondo bawat \r\nproyekto. (Release is entry point for global recovery of multi-million Marcos \r\ndollar and gold deposits for the benefit of the people.) </FONT>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>2. Fair regulation of \r\ntuition fees, gasoline prices, water rates and electric rates thru due process \r\nand after full and fair hearing to avoid arbitrary fees and rates.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>3. Fair increase of salaries \r\nof teachers, soldiers, policemen, workers and public employees after \r\nconsultation without dismissal. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>4. Fair increase of \r\nveterans\' pension not lower than P 5,000/mo.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>5. Low - cost housing for \r\nmedia practitioners, soldiers, policemen, teachers, workers, government \r\nemployees, veterans and Overseas Filipino Workers (OFW\'s).</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>6. Appropriate place of \r\nworship for different religious groups. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>7. Fair and honorable peace \r\naccord with and rehabilitation of our Muslim brothers coupled with economic \r\ndevelopment.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>8. Relocation and \r\nrehabilitation of squatters, street children, and victims of women/child abuse \r\nupang may \"bahay at hanapbuhay\".</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>9. Recreational and \r\nRehabilitation Center for Senior Citizens with complete facilities.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>10. Strengthen the sports \r\nprogram for youth and national athletes.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>11. Even playing fields for \r\ninvestors: No cronyism. No behest loans. </FONT></P>\r\n<P align=center><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>¨ IN ALL THE \r\nABOVEMENTIONED SUBJECTS/PROBLEMS, I HUMBLY SUBMIT MY IMMEDIATE SOLUTION; \r\n</B><BR><BR>THAT IS - THE USE OF THE $647 MILLION MARCOS DEPOSIT WITH THE PNB \r\n(Philippine National Bank) UPON RELEASE FOR THE BENEFIT OF THE FILIPINO PEOPLE \r\nREGARDLESS OF RELIGIOUS OR POLITICAL BELIEFS. LEGISLATION ALONE CANNOT SOLVE THE \r\nECONOMIC CRISIS. </FONT></P>','','','','Dingras Ilocos Norte','','','',2,20010531112842,'','','Oli','',465929,0,403151,'N',44701,6465,43267,61045,6255,10942,5863,5342,3244,7001,16148,4845,9125,0,41048,7132,14);
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES (17,'Madrigal','Ma. Ana','C',243,'candsenator - jamby madrigal.jpg','1958-04-26','','','','','','','Manila','','','',1,20010531112842,'','<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><I><B>A. GENERAL \r\nISSUES</B></I></FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>POVERTY. Need to empower \r\nchildren , enrich their lives through Christian values.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>POPULATION. Responsible \r\nparenthood, with the precepts of Christian values.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>GRAFT AND CORRUPTION. Start \r\nby example. Need for young blood.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ENVIRONMENT AND NATURAL \r\nRESOURCES. Sustainable development. Residents should be encouraged to help \r\nmanage their own environment.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>CRIME PREVENTION. Prevention \r\nof violence at home.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>TERRORISM. All-out war in \r\nMindanao.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ARTS AND CULTURE. \r\nPreservation of Arts and culture for the youth. Amenable to the establishment of \r\na separate Department of Arts and Culture.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>HOUSING. Sustainable \r\nhousing, with access to schools, markets, clinics, etc. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY. The \r\nPhilippines can be competitive.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>REVENUE COLLECTION. Let the \r\nrich pay their taxes.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>JUSTICE SYSTEM. Empowerment \r\nof the poor before they can have justice.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ABOLITION OF ROTC. There is \r\nneed for discipline.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY. \r\nPromotion of and support to science and technology. Provide incentives and give \r\ndue recognition to Filipinos who excel in science and technology.</FONT></P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B><I>B. POLITICAL \r\nISSUES</I></B></FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>GOOD GOVERNANCE. Welfare of \r\nthe majority before anything else. Consultation with the people regarding issues \r\nthat affect all. Encourage transparency in decision making and \r\ngovernance.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>CONSTITUTIONAL REFORMS. \r\nBuild a stable nation first.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>SEPARATION OF CHURCH AND \r\nSTATE. Church should empower the poor.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>PEACE NEGOTIATIONS. Peaceful \r\nsociety towards a developed society. Open our corridors for peace but let us not \r\ncompromise our sovereignty.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>FORM OF GOVERNMENT. Need to \r\nstrengthen the Presidential system by constitutional means.</FONT></P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B><I>C. BUSINESS AND \r\nECONOMY</I></B></FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ECONOMIC REFORMS. Narrow the \r\ngap between the rich and poor. More equitable distribution of wealth.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>OIL DEREGULATION. Fact is, \r\nRP has cheaper oil than other countries.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>PRIVATIZATION. Should be \r\nselective.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>GLOBALIZATION. Need for \r\nsafety nets.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>GATT/WTO. Need for safety \r\nnets; without them, our agriculture will suffer.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>REFORMS IN THE BANKING \r\nSYSTEM. Should proceed slowly, otherwise, there might be capital \r\nflight.</FONT></P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B><I>D. MORAL \r\nISSUES</I></B></FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>FAMILY PLANNING. Responsible \r\nparenthood.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ABORTION. The unborn child \r\nhas a right to live.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>DEATH PENALTY. Against. We \r\nneed proper reforms in our prisons.</FONT></P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B><I>E. SECTORAL \r\nISSUES</I></B></FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>WOMEN. Encourage active \r\nparticipation of women.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ELDERLY. More \r\nprograms.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>INDIGENOUS PEOPLES. More \r\nprograms.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>DISABLED. Need for major \r\nprograms.</FONT></P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B><I>F.CHILDRENS \r\nISSUES</I></B></FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>EDUCATION. Improvement of \r\nthe quality of education for all, with focus on the modernization of facilities \r\nand method of teaching. Proper support should be given to all public school \r\nteachers, to improve the quality of their performance. This would include \r\ntraining and other necessary programs.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>HEALTH AND NUTRITION. Need \r\nfor proper information on health and nutrition. A healthy child can think well \r\nand function properly in school. Healthy population towards a developed society \r\nthrough proper nutrition and health practices. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>CHILD LABOR AND \r\nEXPLOITATION. Anti-child labor and exploitation. Support for bills opposing \r\nchild labor and exploitation.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>DRUG ADDICTION. All-out war \r\nagainst drugs.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>CHILD PROSTITUTION. All-out \r\nwar.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>JUVENILE DELINQUENCY. Reform \r\nin law on juvenile delinquency.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ENVIRONMENT. Clean and \r\nhealthy environment for all. Sustainable economic growth compatible with \r\nenvironmental protection. Promotion of greater responsibility for local \r\ncommunities over their environments, including them in decision making and \r\nmanagement of their resources. Educating people on the importance of sustainable \r\ndevelopment and environment protection.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>CHILD FRIENDLY SOCIETY. \r\nPromotion of the rights of every child. More active participation of children in \r\nthe society. Creation of an environment for children where they can develop \r\ntheir potential and become responsible citizens of society.</FONT></P>','Jamby Madrigal','',4810781,2,3760258,'N',216371,71143,489363,961918,139457,201260,39373,86026,71075,141237,311670,68438,44546,0,349492,103109,114);
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES (18,'Magsaysay','Ramon Jr.','B',465,'candsenator - jun magsaysay.jpg','1938-06-05','','','','','','[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.magsaysay.com/profile/profile-about.htm\">http://www.magsaysay.com/profile/profile-about.htm</A>]<BR><BR>\r\n<P class=newstitle>Carrying on the Legacy</P>\r\n<P class=newstext>Senator Ramon Magsaysay, Jr. is the only son of the late and \r\nbeloved Philippine President Ramon Magsaysay and Mrs. Luz Banzon-Magsaysay. He \r\nwas born in Manila in 1938. He is married to Marilou Kahn-Magsaysay. His two \r\nchildren, Francisco and Margarita, are now both married and with families of \r\ntheir own. \r\n<P class=newstext>His father\'s rise to the presidency in 1953 taught Jun \r\nMagsaysay and his sisters, Milagros and Teresita, the virtues of integrity, \r\nhonesty and having a strong passion for the welfare of the common man. Inside \r\nmajestic Malacañang the Magsaysays lived humbly, untouched by selfish ambitions \r\nand unmarred by lust for power. \r\n<P class=newstitle>An Early Responsibility \r\n<P class=newstext>With President Magsaysay\'s sudden death in 1957,18-year-old \r\nJun inherited greater responsibilities that enabled him to recognize the value \r\nof perseverance and hard work. He was no longer his father\'s boy. Instantly, he \r\nhad to become the man of the house. \r\n<P class=newstitle>Education \r\n<P class=newstext>Jun spent most of his academic years at the De La Salle \r\nCollege in Manila where he earned a degree in Mechanical Engineering. He pursued \r\nhis academic studies at Harvard School of Business Administration in Boston, \r\nMassachusetts and in New York University Graduate School of Business \r\nAdministration. He returned to the Philippines armed with new skills, knowledge, \r\nand vision that would later become a strong force behind the development of a \r\nmajor industry in the country. </P>\r\n<P class=newstitle>Youngest Congressman</P>\r\n<P class=newstext>Being the only son of a revered president, Jun Magsaysay \r\ncarries with him the responsibility of continuing the legacy of championing the \r\ncause of the common man. Thus in 1966 he was elected as a Congressional \r\nRepresentative for the lone district of Zambales. Dubbed as the Benjamin of the \r\nHouse of Representatives, he was the youngest Congressman to be elected to the \r\nLower House at the age of 27. In Congress, he authored and sponsored bills \r\ndesigned to promote the development of science and technology and improve the \r\nwelfare and benefits of private and government workers. Taking after his father, \r\nJun bravely declared his positions on issues that affect the conditions of the \r\ncommon man.</P>\r\n<P class=newstitle>A Man Who Can Say \'No\'</P>\r\n<P class=newstext>In 1969, he ran for re-election under the opposition Liberal \r\nParty. Then First Lady Imelda Marcos offered to endorse his candidacy if he will \r\nleave LP and run under the administration\'s Nacionalista Party. Declining the \r\noffer, Jun Magsaysay stayed with LP and<BR>was defeated by the powerful NP \r\nmachinery which instead drafted his cousin, Antonio Diaz.</P>\r\n<P class=newstitle>Self-Made Businessman</P>\r\n<P class=newstext>After a productive four-year term in Congress he returned to \r\nwork in the private sector where he ventured into various industries including \r\ngarment manufacturing and export, semi-conductor, and travel and tourism. Armed \r\nwith his business education and engineering skills, Jun pioneered the cable \r\ntelevision business in the country. Today, with over 550 cable operators \r\nnationwide, the cable TV industry business has turned into a P2-billion a year \r\nindustry.</P>\r\n<P class=newstitle>Returning to Public Service</P>\r\n<P class=newstext>In 1995, President Ramos invited Jun to join the senatorial \r\nslate of the Lakas-Laban Coalition as a guest LP candidate. He landed third \r\nplace among the twelve elected senators and first among the neophyte candidates. \r\nOnce again the Filipino people elected a Magsaysay to be one of their leaders in \r\ngovernment. They trusted the integrity of the son of their beloved President to \r\ncontinue the legacy of serving the cause of the common man.</P>\r\n<P class=newstitle>J.O.B.S.</P>\r\n<P class=newstext>In the Senate, Jun Magsaysay worked within the objective of \r\nproviding opportunities that would help improve the living conditions of the \r\nordinary Filipino. His program of government is summarized as \'<B>J.O.B.S.</B>\', \r\nthe acronym for Jobs, Opportunities, Business and Security. The laws he helped \r\nenact were geared toward expanding business and employment opportunities, \r\npromoting national unity and security.</P>\r\n<P class=newstitle>Quest for Moral Governance</P>\r\n<P class=newstext>On October 12, 2000, five months before he is to embark on a \r\nre-election bid, Magsaysay resigned from the administration coalition to support \r\nthe people\'s call for the President\'s resignation. His decision to sever ties \r\nwith the administration came in light of clamor for moral governance, with Jun \r\nMagsaysay believing that the President has &amp;quot;lost his moral authority to \r\ngovern the nation&amp;quot;. Once again, Magsaysay had shown that he is ready to \r\nturn his back on a powerful machinery that would have ensured his political \r\nsurvival, in exchange for a reformed and morally upright government.</P>\r\n<P class=newstitle>Mission to Carry on the Legacy</P>\r\n<P class=newstext>Indeed, President Ramon Magsaysay\'s commitment to the \r\nFilipinos did not die with him in that tragic plane crash. His son, Jun \r\nMagsaysay, is living proof that the Filipino people have not entirely lost a \r\ngreat leader, he left behind a son to carry on the legacy.</P>','Manila','','','',2,20010531112842,'','','Jun','',10794941,1,8505158,'N',766343,173870,1204381,1261041,531295,1044442,372306,127899,153399,293513,459032,71352,205735,0,598921,317044,171);
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES (19,'Mercado','Orlando','S',465,'candsenator - orly mercado.jpg','1946-04-26','','','<P><B>S<FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">enator Orly \r\nMercado</FONT></B><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"> believes that the \r\nprimary task of a political leader is to ensure that government serves the \r\ninterest of the people, especially the poor. This can only be achieved through \r\npolicies and programs that will:</FONT></P>\r\n<UL>\r\n<LI><B><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Provide equal opportunity for \r\neconomic activity, education, jobs and livelihood; </FONT></B>\r\n<LI><B><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">improve access to basic \r\nservices such as safe water, housing electricity and health services;</FONT></B> \r\n\r\n<LI><B><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">sustain technology - driven \r\nreforms in management systems of government to minimize graft and corruption and \r\nto ensure transparency and accountability;</FONT></B> \r\n<LI><B><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">conserve environmental \r\nresources </FONT></B>\r\n<LI><B><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">provide peace, order and \r\nsecurity </FONT></B></LI></UL>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">These goals cannot be achieved by \r\ngovernment alone.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Individuals citizens groups, the \r\nmedia, the private sector and the community itself are equally responsible for \r\npolitical change and social transformation. These different stakeholders must \r\nwork together not only for economic development but for a just society where the \r\npoor and other marginalized groups can have more opportunities to improve the \r\nquality of their lives.</FONT></P>','','','','Manila','','','',2,20010531112842,'','','Orly','',7514402,2,5618222,'N',397558,128915,651812,1158270,221990,362780,128508,115425,104728,222836,440604,133746,110727,0,460161,175814,225);
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES (20,'Monsod','Solita','C',267,'candsenator - solita monsod.jpg','1940-07-29','','','','','','[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.marengwinnie.com/resume-content.htm\">http://www.marengwinnie.com/resume-content.htm</A>]<BR><BR>\r\n<BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<P align=center><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica\"><FONT size=3><B><FONT size=2>CURRICULUM \r\nVITAE</FONT></B></FONT></SPAN></FONT></P>\r\n<P align=center><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" \r\nsize=2><B><SPAN style=\"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica\"><FONT \r\nface=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">SOLITAS \r\nCOLLAS-MONSOD</FONT></SPAN></B></FONT></P>\r\n<H1><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica\"><FONT size=1>PERSONAL \r\nINFORMATION</FONT></SPAN></FONT></H1></BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<UL>\r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><FONT size=1>Life \r\npartner of Christian S. Monsod since June 17, 1961.</FONT></FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Mother to Solita \r\nNoemi, teacher, director, and stage actress; Toby Melissa, mathematician, \r\neconomist and community organizer; Teresa Patricia, pediatric endocrinologists, \r\nfelloe at Yale Medical Hospital; Christian Enrique, composer, arranger, sound \r\nengineer and entrepreneur; and Katrina Diane Noelle, senior law student, \r\nassistant coach of Debating Team and choir director, at Ateneo Law \r\nSchool.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Sister to Juan G. \r\nCollas, Anisia Celis, Angela Dean, Diana and Regina.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Daughter to Juan \r\nD. Collas (newspaper, diplomat, author) and</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Soledad Garduno \r\n(teacher, social worker, author), both deceased.</FONT> </LI></UL>\r\n<BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<H1><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><B>W O R K E X P E \r\nR I E N C E</B></FONT></H1>\r\n<H2><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><B>International \r\nExperience</B></FONT></H2>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><FONT \r\nsize=1>Member, UN Committee for Development Planning (UNCDP), 1987-2000.&nbsp; \r\nThe Committee is a high-level advisory group to the UN-ECOSOC, composed of 24 \r\nexperts serving in their personal capacity</FONT></FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Member, Board of \r\nTrustees, International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI) Washington, \r\nJanuary 1996</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Member, Board of \r\nAdvisors, Human Development Report 1993</FONT><FONT \r\nface=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Member, Board of Advisors, \r\nSouth Centre, Geneva, Switzerland, 1991-1995.&nbsp; The South Centre was \r\nestablished to follow-up the ecommendations of the South Commission, organized \r\nin 1987 at the initiative of Prime Minister Mahathir Mohammad of Malaysia and \r\nchaired by Mwalimu Julius Nyerere of Tanzania.&nbsp; The Commission issued a \r\nreport in 1990 entitled <I>The Challenge of the South </I>which has since been \r\ntranslated in five languages.</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<UL>\r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Member, South Commission, \r\n1987-1990.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Member, regional Poverty \r\nAlleviation Group, 1994.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Member, HEDF \r\nInvestment and management Advisory Committee, Commission on Higher Education \r\n(CHED), 1997.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Lecturer, resource \r\nperson, facilitator, panelist in numerous for a, symposia, lectures, meetings \r\ninvolving academic, media, religious, civic and community organizations on \r\nvarious issues of current interest.</FONT> </LI></UL>\r\n<BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<H1><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><B>E D U C A T I O \r\nN</B></FONT></H1></BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<UL>\r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>A.B. Economics \r\n(Cum Laude), University of the Philippines, 1959.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>M.A. Economics, \r\nUniversity of Pennsylvania, 1962</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Ph.D. Economics Candidate \r\n(completed all requirements except dissertation), University of Pennsylvania, \r\n1963.</FONT> </LI></UL>\r\n<BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<H1><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><B>H O N O R S / A \r\nW A R D S</B></FONT></H1></BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<UL>\r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Broadcaster of the \r\nYear, 2000.&nbsp; Award presented by KBP.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Best TV Program Host, Public \r\nAffairs Program.&nbsp; Award presented by Star Awards.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Best Public \r\nAffairs Program, 2000.&nbsp; Award presented by Catholic Mass Media \r\nAwards.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Best TV Program \r\nHost, Public Affairs Program, 1999.&nbsp; Award presented by Star Awards.</FONT> \r\n\r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Woman of Distinction, \r\n1995.&nbsp; Award presented by Soroptimist International Makati.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Woman of the Year, \r\n1988.&nbsp; Award presented by <I>Perspectives</I>, publication of the Catholic \r\nEducators Association of the Philippines.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Cabinet Secretary \r\nof the Year, 1988 and 1999.&nbsp; Award presented by the <I>Philippine Free \r\nPress.</I></FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Professional Award in \r\nEconomics, 1987.&nbsp; Award presented by the University of the Philippines \r\nAlumbni Association.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Mariang Maya \r\nAward.&nbsp; Presented by the Sigma Delta Phi Alumnae Association, University of \r\nthe Philippines.</FONT> </LI></UL>\r\n<BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<H2><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Government \r\nAdministration</FONT></H2></BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<UL>\r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Minister (later \r\nSecretary) of Socio-Economic Planning, Government of the Republic of the \r\nPhilippines, 1986-1989</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Director-General, \r\nNational Economic and Development Authority (NEDA), Government of the Republic \r\nof the Philippines, 1986-1989.&nbsp; Through its central and regional offices \r\nand inter-agency committees, NEDA coordinates the formulation, implementation, \r\nmonitoring, and evaluation of development plans, policies, programmes, and \r\nprojects.</FONT> </LI></UL>\r\n<BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<H2><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Academic \r\nInvolvement</FONT></H2></BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<UL>\r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Professor, School \r\nof Economics, University of the Philippines, 1991-present.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Member \r\n(representing the Faculty), Board of Regents, University of the Philippines, \r\n1991-1992.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Associate \r\nProfessor, School of Economics, University of the Philippines, 1985-1991</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Assistant Professor, School of \r\nEconomics, University of the Philippines, 1971-1984.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Executive \r\nDirector, University of the Philippine Foundation, Inc., 1984-1985.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Economist, <I>Mathematica, \r\n</I>Princeton, New Jersey and Washington D.C., 1965-1970.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Consultant, \r\nEconomic Development Foundation, Manila, Philippines 1964.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Research Fellow, Econometric \r\nResearch Unit, University of Pennsylvania, 1961-1965.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Hiram Haney Fellow, University \r\nof Pennsylvania, 1961-1963.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" \r\nsize=1>Fulbright-Smith-Mundt Scholar, 1961.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Economic Researcher, Economic \r\nDevelopment Consultants, Manila, Philippines, 1960-1961.</FONT> </LI></UL>\r\n<BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<H2><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Other Professional \r\nand Community Involvement</FONT></H2></BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<UL>\r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Conveyor and \r\nChair, Human Development Network, Philippines, 1992-present.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Vice-chairman, \r\nDepartment of Agriculture Senior Scientists Advisory Committee, 2000</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Co-Host, <I>Debate with Mare \r\nat Pare, </I>GMA-7, 1998-present</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Columnist, <I>The \r\nPhilippine Daily Inquirer, </I>2000</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Columnist, \r\n<I>Pinoy Times, </I>1999</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Columnist, \r\n<I>Business World, </I>1996</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Columnist, The Sunday Paper, \r\n2000</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Board Member, \r\nPhilippine American Educational Foundation, 1999</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Board Member, \r\nPhilippines Economic Society, 1998</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Board Member, Claro M. Recto \r\nMemorial Foundation, Philippines.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Board Member, Jose P. Laurel \r\nFoundation.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Board Member, \r\nBatibot Children’s TV, Philippines.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Board Member, \r\nFellows of the Asia Foundation, 1991-1997</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>Member, People’s Fact-Finding \r\nCommittee on Agrarian Reform, Philippines, 1991-1992</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Co-Host, <I>Firing \r\nLine,</I> GMA-7, 1995-1998</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Columnist, \r\nPhilippine Daily Star, 1990-October 1996</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Board Member, \r\nSocial Housing Foundation, Philippines.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Chair for Fort \r\nBonifacio, National Movement for Free Elections (NAMFREL)), 1996</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Co-Chair for Metro \r\nManila, NAMFREL, 1984</FONT> </LI></UL>\r\n<BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<H1><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" \r\nsize=1>PUBLICATION</FONT></H1></BLOCKQUOTE>\r\n<UL>\r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>“International and \r\nIntranational Comparisons of Philippine Poverty”, Causes of Poverty: Myths, \r\nFacts &amp; Policies, a Philippine Study.&nbsp; Edited by Arsenio M. Balisacan \r\nand Shigeaki Fujisaki. Diliman, Up Press, 1999.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Philippine \r\nPoverty: A Status Report – Asia Society, 1997.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN>“Engendering \r\nDevelopment”.&nbsp; Quezon City: Rafael M. Salas Foundation, 1995.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>“Debt or \r\nDevelopment: Philippine Imperatives and the Conventional Strategy for Debt \r\nManagement,” <I>Perspective of the Pacific Basic Economy: A Comparison of Asia \r\nand Latin America.</I>&nbsp; Edited by Takao Fukuchi and Mitsuhiro Kagami.&nbsp; \r\nTokyo: The Asian Club Foundation and Institute of Developing Economies, \r\n1990.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol\"><SPAN \r\nstyle=\"FONT: 7pt \'Times New Roman\'\"></SPAN></SPAN><I>“Management of the Debt \r\nCrisis: A Debtor’s Viewpoint,”</I> Solving the Global Debt Crisis: Strategies \r\nand Controversies by Key Stakeholders.&nbsp; Edited by Christine A. \r\nBogdanowics-Bindert.&nbsp; New York: Harper &amp; Row, 1989.</FONT> \r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Fiscal Policy and \r\nthe Philippine Economy.&nbsp; SEANZA Central Banking Course, Nepal, 1985.</FONT> \r\n\r\n<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>An Analysis of the \r\nPhilippine Economic Crisis.&nbsp; (Co-Author).&nbsp; Quezon City: University of \r\nthe Philippines, 1984.<BR><BR></FONT><FONT \r\nface=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><BR></FONT></LI></UL>','Manila','','','',2,20010531112842,'','','Mareng Winnie','',6418224,1,5052302,'N',396234,70377,801345,786630,289605,5